<rss version="2.0" xmlns:atom="http://www.w3.org/2005/Atom"><channel><title><![CDATA[WSJ - EN-US - world]]></title><link/> https://www.wsj.com/news/world <atom:link href="https://rsshub.app/wsj/en-us/world" rel="self" type="application/rss+xml"></atom:link><description><![CDATA[WSJ - EN-US - world - Made with love by RSSHub(https://github.com/DIYgod/RSSHub)]]></description><generator> RS集线器</generator><webmaster>i@diygod.me (DIYgod)</webmaster><language> zh-cn</language><lastbuilddate> 2023 年 7 月 27 日星期四 13:15:14 GMT</lastbuilddate><ttl> 120 </ttl><item><title><![CDATA[Israeli Protesters Pledge to Intensify Civil Unrest]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div>计划于周四举行大规模示威，运动领导人表示他们正在从“遏制转向进攻” <!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001089294"><div class="is-lead-inset"><div class="media-object scope-
          header
"><figure class="media-object-image img-header"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="860" height="574" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-824744?width=860&amp;height=574" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">周一，抗议者封锁了耶路撒冷以色列议会大楼外的一条道路。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：Kobi Wolf/彭博新闻</p></figcaption></figure></div></div></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001089294"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline"> <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/dov-lieber" itemprop="url" rel="author">多夫·利伯</a></span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1">美国东部时间 2023 年 7 月 27 日上午 7:00 </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/israeli-protesters-pledge-to-intensify-civil-unrest-76b69af9"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><p>特拉维夫——以色列抗议领导人周四宣布在特拉维夫举行大规模示威，这是针对总理本杰明·内塔尼亚胡的<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/israel-protests-judicial-overhaul-netanyahu-7e264a71?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">司法改革</a>而增加骚乱的新计划的一部分。</p><p>这次抗议活动发生在犹太日历上最阴沉的斋戒日之一——Tisha B&#39;Av，纪念耶路撒冷第一座和第二座古庙被毁，以及历史上其他伟大的犹太悲剧。抗议组织者利用禁食的时机，称内塔尼亚胡正在造成犹太家园的第三次破坏。</p><p>以色列物理学家、抗议运动领导人之一希克马·布雷斯勒 (Shikma Bressler) 表示：“一切合法和非暴力的事情都可以讨论。”布雷斯勒表示，这可能意味着更多的罢工以及主要高速公路和公共交通的中断。</p><p>周一，以色列议会<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/israel-netanyahu-government-judicial-overhaul-protests-862dffd3?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">通过了一项更广泛计划的第一部分</a>，以限制最高法院的权力并将更多控制权交给立法者。</p><p>该计划的支持者表示，法院由自由派法官控制，他们太快地推翻了人民的意愿，必须加以控制，以恢复政府各部门之间的适当平衡。反对者表示，此举旨在削弱法院，以便内塔尼亚胡的右翼、极端民族主义和<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/israel-ultra-orthodox-haredim-military-service-supreme-court-of-ultra-orthodox-jews-shakes-israels-sense-of-identity-b3155e01?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">宗教保守派政党</a>联盟能够制定破坏以色列自由民主的立法，并通过践踏少数群体权利并将更多宗教强加于公共领域的立法。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><div class="media-object-video"><div class="wsj-media-summary clearfix"><div class="strap-container"><h4 class="strap" itemprop="description"></h4></div></div><iframe width="400" height="225" src="https://video-api.wsj.com/api-video/player/v3/iframe.html?guid=B58B7540-4CF9-464C-A04F-C0E71926FD01&amp;height=225&amp;width=400&amp;plid=video_amp&amp;chainVideos=true&amp;parentUrl=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.wsj.com%2Famp%2Farticles%2Fisraeli-protesters-pledge-to-intensify-civil-unrest-76b69af9&amp;a=a" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe><p class="imageCaption">以色列医生周二举行罢工，当局在因总理本杰明·内塔尼亚胡政府进行的司法改革而发生骚乱的夜晚，强行将抗议者从道路上带走。照片：阿米尔·利维/盖蒂图片社<span class="imageCredit">
        
        
        </span></p></div></div><p>内塔尼亚胡和他的盟友表示，他们正在执行选民的意愿。一些联盟成员将一些抗议者视为无政府主义者。</p><p>内塔尼亚胡周一在向全国发表讲话时表示，“执行选民的意愿绝不是‘民主的终结’”。 “这是民主的本质。”</p><p>议会于 7 月 30 日开始夏季休会，直到 10 月中旬才会返回。内塔尼亚胡表示，他将在秋季继续推进改革，但在春季和夏季谈判失败后将寻求与反对派妥协。</p><p> “反对派不会参与一场空洞的谈判，”以色列反对派领导人亚伊尔·拉皮德周一晚间表示。</p><p>周一，该法律通过之前和之后都发生了大规模示威活动，并持续到深夜。在投票前，抗议者试图阻止进入耶路撒冷议会。投票通过后，抗议者封锁了全国各地的高速公路，并与警察发生冲突。</p><p>但到了周二，事情已经基本平静下来，目前尚不清楚抗议运动下一步将走向何方。一些领导人表示，他们仍在策划如何充分发动和维持这场运动。</p><p>周三晚上，主要抗议团体之一卡普兰部队宣布，该运动正在从“遏制转向进攻”，并称内塔尼亚胡政府“非法”。该组织以特拉维夫卡普兰街命名，那里连续 29 周发生了反对司法计划的大规模示威活动。</p><p>支持司法立法的右翼团体也不时大量站出来，尽管自立法通过以来并没有出现大规模的支持改革的示威活动。该计划的许多支持者表示，他们觉得该法律的通过是正确的。</p><p>据组织者称，在以色列这个拥有 930 万人口的县，抗议运动有时导致多达 50 万人走上街头。该组织由预备役军人、前安全官员、商业和科技行业领袖、公共知识分子以及通过 WhatsApp 组织的青年组织领导。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="466" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-824745?width=700&amp;height=466" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">一名以色列预备役军人签署了暂停志愿服务的承诺，以响应司法改革的通过。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：阿米尔·科恩/路透社</p></figcaption></figure></div><p>如果立法获得通过， <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/israels-judicial-overhaul-raises-security-concerns-as-reservists-refuse-to-serve-5d68bfff?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">数千名预备役军人</a>将拒绝报到，威胁的全面情况仍不清楚。周二，以色列军方发言人丹尼尔·哈加里表示，预备役军人停止服役的要求有所增加。虽然军队的作战能力尚未受到损害，但他表示，如果这种趋势持续下去，这种情况可能会发生。</p><p>内塔尼亚胡表示，拒绝服役是一种非法的抗议形式。</p><p>代表预备役军人的“兄弟连”组织的领导人之一罗恩·谢尔夫表示，他们将把示威活动的重点放在内塔尼亚胡和国防部长约阿夫·加兰特身上，他们认为他们对破坏军队团结负有主要责任。</p><p> “在任何有独裁者的国家，人民军队都行不通，”他说。</p><p>布雷斯勒表示，前七个月的抗议活动唤醒了以色列的自由民主阵营，他们“没有意识到自己的规模和力量”。她说，现在她正在考虑如何发挥这个营地的潜力。她还指出，过去一周，参加示威活动的年轻抗议者数量大幅增加，导致示威活动更加激烈，并导致与警察发生冲突。</p><p>写信给 Dov Lieber，邮箱为<a href="mailto:dov.lieber@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">dov.lieber@wsj.com</a></p></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Thu, 27 Jul 2023 11:00:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/israeli-protesters-pledge-to-intensify-civil-unrest-76b69af9</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/israeli-protesters-pledge-to-intensify-civil-unrest-76b69af9<author><![CDATA[Dov Lieber]]></author><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>内乱</category><category>国家/公共安全</category><category>社会/社区</category><category>政治/国际关系</category><category>国内政治</category><category>风险新闻</category><category>社会问题</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category>本杰明·内塔尼亚胡</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>内乱</category><category>国家的</category><category>公安</category><category>社会</category><category>社区</category><category>政治</category><category>国际关系</category><category>国内政治</category><category>风险新闻</category><category>社会问题</category></item><item><title><![CDATA[Military Officers Say They Removed Niger’s President]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div>华盛顿将西非国家视为对抗伊斯兰恐怖和俄罗斯在萨赫勒地区推进的堡垒<!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001086918"><div class="is-lead-inset"><div class="media-object scope-
          header
"><figure class="media-object-image img-header"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="860" height="645" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-824272?width=860&amp;height=645" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">尼日尔总统的支持者聚集在首都尼亚美，有报道称发生了未遂政变。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：法新社/盖蒂图片社</p></figcaption></figure></div></div></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001086918"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline">作者： <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/benoit-faucon" itemprop="url" rel="author">伯努瓦·福肯 (Benoit Faucon)</a></span>和<span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/michael-m-phillips" itemprop="url" rel="author">迈克尔·M·菲利普斯 (Michael M. Phillips)</a></span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1">更新于 2023 年 7 月 27 日凌晨 3:25（东部时间） </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/apparent-coup-attempt-hits-u-s-ally-niger-e3efa36d"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><p>内罗毕——西非国家尼日尔的一群军官周三晚间声称，他们推翻了民选总统，动摇了美国在打击基地组织、伊斯兰国和博科圣地方面最可靠的盟友之一。</p><p>周三晚间，一名尼日尔官员在国家电视台发表讲话时表示，一个名为“国家拯救祖国委员会”的组织夺取了权力，并罢免了尼日尔总统穆罕默德·巴祖姆。</p><p> “我们，国防和安全部队……已经决定结束你所知道的政权，”政变发言人阿马杜·阿卜杜拉马内上校说。阿卜杜拉马内身边有另外九名警官，他引用了他所说的尼日尔安全局势不断恶化的情况。他宣布该国边界已被封锁并实行宵禁，但承诺尊重人权。</p><p>针对 2021 年当选的巴祖姆的叛乱是袭击西非，尤其是萨赫勒地区的最新动荡。萨赫勒地区位于撒哈拉以南的半干旱地区，近年来，伊斯兰恐怖分子在那里杀害了数千名平民。</p><p>自2020年以来，马里、布基纳法索和几内亚都出现了被军官罢黜的民选政府。由于对美国军事援助的法律限制，政变迫使美国在这三个国家停止了军事训练。</p><p>与尼日尔接壤的马里和布基纳法索此后与莫斯科发展了更密切的关系。马里于 2021 年雇佣了俄罗斯瓦格纳集团的雇佣兵，布基纳法索今年早些时候驱逐了支持其打击入侵的暴力伊斯兰组织的法国军队。</p><p>政变领导人在尼日尔国家电视台上发表的声明表明，周三凌晨开始的叛乱已经获得了巨大的支持。据一位与总统关系密切的人士透露，心怀不满的总统卫队早些时候曾对巴祖姆发动叛乱，并包围了他的官邸。该人士表示：“这是一种不满的表达，后来升级为政变企图。”</p><p>周四上午，巴祖姆在社交媒体平台 X（前身为 Twitter）上发布的一条消息中表示，“来之不易的（民主）成果将得到维护。”正在国外旅行的巴祖姆外交部长哈苏米·马苏杜在另一篇帖子中表示，他现在是政府的临时首脑，并表示“尼日尔正在发动政变”，是由“派系官员”进行的。</p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          wrap
"></div><p>与总统关系密切的人士称，忠诚的军队正在巴祖姆家外与政变策划者进行谈判，迫使他们交出武器。总统办公室发布推文称，如果总统卫队不退缩，军队和国民警卫队“已准备好攻击他们”。</p><p>美国在尼日尔阿加德兹镇设有一个无人机基地，以帮助阻止伊斯兰武装分子在萨赫勒地区的蔓延。美国突击队在尼日尔全国各地的前哨基地训练尼日尔特种部队。美国军队过去常常伴随当地同行执行战斗任务，直到 2017 年伊斯兰国伏击导致四名美国士兵死亡。现在，美国人在行动中从远处为尼日尔突击队提供建议。</p><p>针对巴祖姆的武装叛乱立即引起了国际社会的谴责。</p><p>美国驻联合国大使琳达·托马斯·格林菲尔德</p>表示，“美国强烈谴责任何以武力夺取政权、破坏尼日尔宪法秩序的行为。”<p></p><p> “我们呼吁立即释放总统穆罕默德·巴祖姆。我们呼吁尊重法治和公共安全，”她在周三晚上的一条<a href="https://twitter.com/usambun/status/1684343770358194176" target="_blank" class="icon none" rel="noopener">推文</a>中说道。</p><p>国务卿安东尼·布林肯在与巴祖姆通话后表示，美国“严重关注”尼日尔的事态发展。</p><p> “我们正在密切关注尼日尔的局势和事态发展，”他于当地时间周四在新西兰惠灵顿对记者表示。 “我们谴责任何以武力夺取政权的行为。我们正在积极与尼日尔政府以及该地区和世界各地的合作伙伴进行接触，并将继续这样做，直到局势得到适当、和平的解决。” </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="467" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-824275?width=700&amp;height=467" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">尼日尔总统穆罕默德·巴祖姆上个月在巴黎举行的一次聚会上。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：卢多维奇·马林/路透社</p></figcaption></figure></div><p>他补充说，美国大使馆正在清查其人员和家属的情况，为局势可能恶化做好准备。他说，美国与尼日尔的安全伙伴关系取决于这一局势的结果。</p><p>非洲联盟委员会主席穆萨·法基·穆罕默德指责策划者“完全背叛了共和义务”。</p><p>由 15 国组成的西非国家经济共同体发表声明，称其执行委员会“以最强烈的措辞谴责企图以武力夺取政权的行为，并呼吁政变策划者立即无条件释放民选共和国总统。”</p><p>尼日尔驻华盛顿大使基亚里·利曼-廷吉里 (Kiari Liman-Tinguiri) 将这次起义称为“破坏我们民主运作的企图”。他在推文中补充道：“不会向总统卫队的不诚实官员妥协。”</p><p>美国将巴祖姆领导下的尼日尔视为抵御<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/u-s-builds-new-firewall-to-stop-spread-of-militant-islamists-11670771719?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">萨赫勒地区伊斯兰武装分子</a>迅速蔓延的防火墙。萨赫勒地区是撒哈拉以南的半干旱地区。尼日尔也是该地区罕见的盟友，该地区的一些国家已经转而反对华盛顿及其西方伙伴，转而与<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/kremlins-wagner-shake-up-rattles-nerves-in-africa-middle-east-8c917a97?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">俄罗斯和瓦格纳集团</a>雇佣军建立了更密切的关系。</p><p class="articleTagLine"> —William Mauldin 和 Vivian Salama 对本文做出了贡献。</p><p>写信给 Michael M. Phillips ( <a href="mailto:Michael.Phillips@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">Michael.Phillips@wsj.com)</a>和 Benoit Faucon ( <a href="mailto:benoit.faucon@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">benoit.faucon@wsj.com</a> )</p></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Thu, 27 Jul 2023 07:25:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/apparent-coup-attempt-hits-us-ally-niger-e3efa36d</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/apparent-coup-attempt-hits-us-ally-niger-e3efa36d<author><![CDATA[Benoit FauconMichael M. Phillips]]></author><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>国家/公共安全</category><category>叛乱</category><category>犯罪/法律诉讼</category><category>武装部队</category><category>国际关系</category><category>政治/国际关系</category><category>国内政治</category><category>风险新闻</category><category>恐怖主义</category><category>军事行动</category><category>内容类型</category><category>法激活过滤器</category><category>C&amp;E 行政新闻过滤器</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category>基亚里·利曼-廷吉里</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>国家的</category><category>公安</category><category>叛乱</category><category>犯罪</category><category>合法举动</category><category>武装部队</category><category>国际关系</category><category>政治</category><category>国内政治</category><category>风险新闻</category><category>恐怖主义</category><category>军事行动</category><category>内容类型</category><category>法蒂瓦过滤器</category><category>C&amp;E 行政新闻过滤器</category></item><item><title><![CDATA[Russian Attack on U.S. Drone Spurs Fears of Escalation Over Syria]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div>美国官员称俄罗斯本周损坏了两架美国无人机<!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001088457"><div class="is-lead-inset"><div class="media-object scope-
          header
"><figure class="media-object-image img-header"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="860" height="573" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-824487?width=860&amp;height=573" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">周日，一架俄罗斯喷气式战斗机在叙利亚上空飞近一架美国无人机。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：美国空军/美联社</p></figcaption></figure></div></div></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001088457"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline">作者： <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/michael-r-gordon" itemprop="url" rel="author">迈克尔·R·戈登</a></span>和<span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/nancy-a-youssef" itemprop="url" rel="author">南希·A·优素福</a></span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1">美国东部时间 2023 年 7 月 27 日上午 12:01 </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/russian-attack-on-u-s-drone-spurs-fears-of-escalation-over-syria-ff3b9f98"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><p>尽管全世界的注意力都集中在俄罗斯对乌克兰的入侵上，但俄罗斯对美国无人机的新攻击使叙利亚成为莫斯科和华盛顿之间军事竞争的一个充满争议的舞台。</p><p>周三，一架俄罗斯喷气式战斗机投下照明弹，损坏了一架飞机的机翼，凸显了冲突的风险。 <strong>&nbsp;</strong>美国官员称，美国 MQ-9“死神”无人机飞越叙利亚西北部上空。</p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          wrap
"></div><p>周三发生的事件是在周日发生的一起事件之后发生的，当时<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/russian-jet-fighter-damages-u-s-drone-over-syria-3be72019?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">另一架 MQ-9 被损坏</a>，美国官员认为，这是俄罗斯协同努力向美军施压，要求其从叙利亚撤军。</p><p>两架美国无人机均成功返回基地。</p><p>无人机并不是最近几周俄罗斯飞行员骚扰的唯一飞机。 7月16日，一架俄罗斯战斗机如此靠近一架飞机<strong>&nbsp;</strong>美国驻中东空军最高将领亚历克苏斯·格林克维奇中将在一份声明中表示，美国涡轮螺旋桨飞机在必须飞过湍流的喷射气流时，美国机组人员面临危险。</p><p>周日事件发生后，五角大楼公开抱怨俄罗斯骚扰美国无人机的行为不专业，并发布了一段视频，展示了这场紧张的遭遇。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="466" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-824491?width=700&amp;height=466" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">周日，一架美国无人机的螺旋桨受损。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：美国空军/美联社</p></figcaption></figure></div><p>在美国强调了他们周日损坏MQ-9螺旋桨的行动后，美国原本希望俄罗斯能够克制一下，但周三的新对抗却让美国人失望了。</p><p>在3月份的类似事件中，俄罗斯也没有任何悔悟的迹象，当时俄罗斯战斗机在黑海上空骚扰了一架MQ-9无人机，严重损坏了螺旋桨，美国被迫将其坠入下面的水域。俄罗斯国防部表示，在此事件中，俄罗斯国防部长谢尔盖·绍伊古向涉案的两名飞行员颁发了奖项。 <strong>&nbsp;</strong></p><p>周三，一名俄罗斯军方官员将责任归咎于美国，称美国无人机对两架俄罗斯飞机进行了“危险接近”，促使飞机通过释放照明弹进行防御性反应。 “美国继续向国际社会误导”，奥列格·古里诺夫少将</p>说。<p></p><p>退休。 2019年至2022年负责美国在中东军事行动的美国中央司令部司令、海军陆战队上将弗兰克·麦肯齐表示，莫斯科的战略是在美国在中东的军事足迹非常有限的情况下，试图从叙利亚撤回美军。</p><p>麦肯齐说，“他们想让游戏变得太丰富，让我们无法玩，这样我们就会退出而不是坚持我们的立场”。 “俄罗斯人倾向于通过升级来缓和局势。”</p><p>莫斯科的行动促使美国官员考虑如果俄罗斯成功击落一架美国无人机，如何应对，包括通过非军事手段。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><div class="media-object-video"><div class="wsj-media-summary clearfix"><div class="strap-container"><h4 class="strap" itemprop="description"></h4></div></div><iframe width="400" height="225" src="https://video-api.wsj.com/api-video/player/v3/iframe.html?guid=3912093C-EDC6-4EDE-806D-57C558C8E8DB&amp;height=225&amp;width=400&amp;plid=video_amp&amp;chainVideos=true&amp;parentUrl=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.wsj.com%2Famp%2Farticles%2Frussian-attack-on-u-s-drone-spurs-fears-of-escalation-over-syria-ff3b9f98&amp;a=a" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe><p class="imageCaption">自乌克兰反攻开始以来，乌克兰大量使用廉价第一人称视角无人机对俄罗斯坦克和大型武器进行神风特攻队式攻击。图片插图：杰里米·舒巴克<span class="imageCredit">
        
        
        </span></p></div></div><p>“这当然是我们更加关注的事情，”一名国防官员表示。</p><p>美国军方周三表示，十几架先进的F-35战斗机已抵达中东，其任务是阻止伊朗对霍尔木兹海峡航运的袭击。但是<strong>&nbsp;</strong>美国军方还在声明中指出，这些飞机“如果需要，可以在整个战区的有争议空域飞行”，指的是美国正在进行的击败伊斯兰国的任务。</p><p>自2015年俄罗斯军队部署支持叙利亚总统巴沙尔·阿萨德以来，叙利亚两军之间一直存在紧张局势</p>在他对对手的残酷竞选中。<p></p><p>美国在叙利亚仍有约 900 名士兵，协助当地合作伙伴库尔德人领导的叙利亚民主力量打击伊斯兰国残余势力。但这些美军正在东部行动，远离疑似伊斯兰国和基地组织领导人活动的西北飞地。</p><p>美国此前曾在叙利亚西北部使用过无人机，多年来，两军一直通过将俄罗斯驻叙利亚指挥官与美国驻该地区指挥官联系起来的冲突消除渠道，成功避免了直接冲突。</p><p> 11月，俄罗斯向叙利亚上空的一架无人机发射了一枚地对空导弹，但未能击落飞机。据美国军方官员称，本月早些时候， <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/russian-jets-confront-u-s-drones-over-syria-b74be68a?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">俄罗斯飞机连续几天骚扰美国 MQ-9 飞机</a>，并驾驶一架 An-30 侦察机飞越叙利亚东南部的美国前哨基地。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="428" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-824497?width=700&amp;height=428" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">美国军方周三表示，十几架先进的 F-35 喷气式战斗机已抵达中东，以阻止伊朗对霍尔木兹海峡航运的袭击。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：鲍里斯·罗斯勒/祖玛出版社</p></figcaption></figure></div><p>有几个因素导致紧张局势加剧。首先，两支军队陷入了任务冲突，因为美军试图追击伊斯兰国残余分子，该组织的领导人隐藏在叙利亚西北部，俄罗斯飞机一直在该地区活动，但远离叙利亚东部，美军一直在该地区与当地盟友合作。</p><p>另一个因素是，由于美国缩减了在该地区的军事足迹，该地区的力量平衡发生了变化。美国派F-22战机飞越叙利亚的日子已经一去不复返了，美国只有更少的战机来试图反击驻扎在叙利亚的俄罗斯飞机。</p><p>美国官员表示，另一个因素是俄罗斯军队在叙利亚日益咄咄逼人的姿态。周日击落一架美国无人机的俄罗斯战斗机上涂有“Z”符号，俄罗斯部队在入侵乌克兰时曾使用过该符号。</p><p>卡内基国际和平基金会的安德鲁·韦斯表示：“俄罗斯人想要进行恐吓，破坏美国不会受到挑战的感觉。” “美国在保护地面和空中人民的同时，试图不上钩。”</p><p>写信给 Michael R. Gordon（ <a href="mailto:michael.gordon@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">michael.gordon@wsj.com</a> ）和 Nancy A. Youssef（ <a href="mailto:nancy.youssef@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">nancy.youssef@wsj.com</a> ）</p></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Thu, 27 Jul 2023 04:01:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/ Russian-attack-on-us-drone-spurs-fears-of-escalation-over-syria-ff3b9f98</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/ Russian-attack-on-us-drone-spurs-fears-of-escalation-over-syria-ff3b9f98<author><![CDATA[Michael R. GordonNancy A. Youssef]]></author><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>国家/公共安全</category><category>武装部队</category><category>国际关系</category><category>政治/国际关系</category><category>风险新闻</category><category>军事行动</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>国家的</category><category>公安</category><category>武装部队</category><category>国际关系</category><category>政治</category><category>风险新闻</category><category>军事行动</category></item><item><title><![CDATA[Hunter Biden Pleads Not Guilty to Tax Charges]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div>法官推迟在法庭听证会上考虑认罪协议<!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001086059"><div class="is-lead-inset"><div class="media-object scope-
          header
"><div class="media-object-video"><div class="wsj-media-summary clearfix"><div class="strap-container"><h4 class="strap" itemprop="description"></h4></div></div><iframe width="400" height="225" src="https://video-api.wsj.com/api-video/player/v3/iframe.html?guid=0B3DB0F9-BB08-44C5-9D27-7C99347D4C8F&amp;height=225&amp;width=400&amp;plid=video_amp&amp;chainVideos=true&amp;parentUrl=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.wsj.com%2Famp%2Farticles%2Fhunter-biden-plea-deal-in-jeopardy-ff556d70&amp;a=a" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe><p class="imageCaption">照片：安娜·钱梅梅克/盖蒂图片社<span class="imageCredit">
        
        
        </span></p></div></div></div></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001086059"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline">作者： <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/sadie-gurman" itemprop="url" rel="author">Sadie Gurman</a></span>和<span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/aruna-viswanatha" itemprop="url" rel="author">Aruna Viswanatha</a></span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1">更新于 2023 年 7 月 26 日下午 5:21（美国东部时间） </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/hunter-biden-plea-deal-in-jeopardy-ff556d70"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><p>特拉华州威尔明顿——周三，亨特·拜登对税务指控表示不认罪，在法官表示亨特·拜登尚未准备好接受<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/hunter-biden-guilty-plea-federal-court-3b15f98b?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">他与检察官达成的认罪协议</a>后，情况发生了惊人的逆转。</p><p>在一场持续三个小时的激烈听证会上，拜登总统之子的一名律师最初与检察官就未来指控的可能性发生争执。在双方澄清<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/hunter-bidens-messy-path-to-a-plea-deal-c22bd962?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">协议</a>后，美国地区法官玛丽莲·诺雷卡表示，她需要更多信息才能决定是否签署协议。</p><div class="media-object scope-web,mobileapps
          wrap
"></div><p> “这些协议并不简单，它们包含非典型条款，”她说，并补充道：“我无法决定接受或拒绝认罪协议，我需要推迟它。”</p><p>被前总统<a href="https://www.wsj.com/topics/person/donald-trump">唐纳德·特朗普</a>任命为法官的诺雷卡法官的最后一刻的剧变，标志着司法部对亨特·拜登的财务、商业交易以及有据可查的毒瘾和酗酒成瘾的曲折且具有政治爆炸性的调查的最新转折。</p><p>几周前公开的认罪协议大纲使亨特·拜登有可能将法律麻烦抛在脑后，尽管国会山的共和党人已经升级了对他涉嫌不当行为的听证会和指控，并试图在拜登总统发起<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/biden-touts-job-growth-in-first-re-election-campaign-rally-9337f3c2?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">连任竞选</a>时将其与他联系起来。</p><p>检察官保留了未来对亨特·拜登提出指控的可能性，包括与司法部长期以来一直在审查的外国游说法有关的指控。周三的结果意味着他的法律困境仍然存在，并且随着 2024 年竞选活动的推进，可能会为众议院和参议院的共和党人提供新的素材。</p><p>众议院议长凯文·麦卡锡（加利福尼亚州共和党）表示，众议院可能会对拜登总统进行弹劾调查，理由是亨特·拜登的海外商业交易涉及腐败。</p><p>白宫一直表示，拜登总统没有与他的儿子讨论亨特·拜登的商业往来，也没有参与其中。参议院多数党领袖查克·舒默（纽约州民主党人）表示：“我对检方有信心……任何人都不应在政治、意识形态上干涉此事，让正义得以伸张。” </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="466" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-824383?width=700&amp;height=466" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">亨特·拜登在特拉华州威尔明顿举行认罪听证会后离开联邦法院。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：乔纳森·恩斯特/路透社</p></figcaption></figure></div><p>如果负责此案的法官最终不宽恕认罪协议，亨特·拜登将面临目前针对他的指控的审判，就像共和党 2024 年总统候选人领先者特朗普面临司法部<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/donald-trump-indicted-in-document-case-b4e563d7?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">指控他处理机密信息不当一样</a>。预计特朗普还将因涉嫌破坏 2020 年大选而被起诉。特朗普否认有任何不当行为。</p><p>小拜登原本预计会承认<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/hunter-biden-charged-with-tax-crimes-bd2dea0a?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">轻罪税务指控</a>，并已达成协议以避免枪支指控。共和党人指责司法部给予拜登一项宽松的协议，这是其他处于类似情况下的人永远不会得到的。该部门否认有任何偏袒。</p><p>在听证会上，亨特·拜登和他的律师坐在一起，静静地看着诉讼程序展开。他透露了自己的康复情况，并告诉法官，在过去的二十年里，他因吸毒和酗酒至少接受了六次治疗。他说，他最后一次吸毒或酗酒是在 2019 年 6 月。</p><p>白宫新闻秘书卡琳·让-皮埃尔周三下午对记者说：“亨特·拜登是一名普通公民，这对他来说是个人问题。” “正如我们所说，总统和第一夫人，他们爱他们的儿子，并将继续支持他重建生活。” </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="466" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-824384?width=700&amp;height=466" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">执法人员保护了特拉华州威尔明顿联邦法院周围地区的安全。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：乔纳森·恩斯特/路透社</p></figcaption></figure></div><p>这场骚乱始于周三，当时检察官利奥·怀斯坚称对亨特·拜登活动的调查仍在进行中，并在回答法官的问题时表示，他可能面临更多的外国游说指控。</p><p>对此，亨特·拜登的律师克里斯·克拉克表示，他不同意这种解释，并认为该协议排除了额外指控的可能性，并随后补充道：“就我而言，认罪协议是无效的。”</p><p>休会后，亨特·拜登的法律团队表示，该协议涵盖了他在 2014 年至 2019 年期间与税务犯罪相关的责任，并涵盖了毒品和枪支犯罪。法官问亨特·拜登是否曾承诺提供任何其他保护措施来诱使他认罪，他说：“没有，法官大人。”</p><p>然后，法官就协议的两个方面中包含的条款向双方施压，包括为什么税收协议是根据一项取消法院审查能力的法规提出的，而枪支协议则包括要求法院判定亨特·拜登是否违反了协议。诺雷卡法官表示，这可能会让她不恰当地做出通常由检察官做出的决定。</p><p> “我对这项规定的合宪性感到担忧，所以我对这项协议的合宪性感到担忧，”她说。</p><p>法官给了双方 30 天的时间来澄清她的角色并提供更多信息。届时，亨特·拜登可以认罪并将他谈判达成的协议正式化。</p><p>亨特·拜登在听证会结束后走出法院走向一辆等候的SUV时没有发表任何评论。</p><p>周二，众议院筹款委员会共和党主席、众议员贾森·史密斯（密苏里州共和党）就此案提交了一份不同寻常的简报，敦促法院考虑拒绝认罪协议。它强调了他的小组最近从两名国税局调查员那里听到的证词，称政治考虑可能影响了调查。简报称：“为了所有公民的完全透明和公平，法院掌握这些信息至关重要。” </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="466" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-824385?width=700&amp;height=466" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">共和党众议员贾森·史密斯就亨特·拜登案提交了一份简报，敦促法院考虑拒绝认罪协议。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：Rod Lamkey/Zuma Press</p></figcaption></figure></div><p>诺雷卡法官表示，她没有时间全面审查这份冗长的申请。</p><p>与联邦检察官达成的协议本应标志着特拉华州美国检察官戴维·韦斯(David Weiss)长达一年的调查的高潮。韦斯是由特朗普任命的，在拜登政府期间一直留任，以彻底完成对总统儿子的刑事调查。作为协议的一部分，检察官同意，只要亨特·拜登保持不吸毒并同意不再拥有枪支，就不会对持有枪支提起单独的重罪指控。</p><p>共和党人承诺继续推进<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/hunter-biden-tries-to-end-legal-woes-as-republicans-vow-to-keep-probing-4b6ac7e9?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">自己的调查</a>，旨在通过拜登总统的儿子来污蔑他，并在 2024 年选举周期升温之际让他的麻烦成为焦点。</p><p>众议院监督委员会主席詹姆斯·科默（肯塔基州共和党人）周三表示：“我们将继续追踪拜登父子的资金轨迹。”他赞扬法官“拒绝对这一“甜心交易”盖章。</p><p>民主党人将共和党领导的调查视为政治表演，监督委员会高级成员众议员杰米·拉斯金（马里兰州民主党人）称其为“检查员克鲁索式的对不存在事物的探索”。</p><p>韦斯的办公室同意建议仅缓刑，作为亨特·拜登认罪协议的一部分，但法官拥有最终决定权。亨特·拜登每项罪名最高可被判处 12 个月监禁和 10 万美元罚款。如果亨特·拜登未能兑现不拥有枪支和不吸毒的承诺，枪支指控最高可判处 10 年监禁和巨额罚款。</p><p>该调查于 2018 年开始，首先审查了小拜登的海外商业交易，但近年来，调查重点转向了他的纳税情况以及他在购买枪支表格上的虚假声明，即他没有使用毒品或吸毒成瘾。亨特·拜登在 2021 年的回忆录《美丽的事物》中详细描述了他长期吸毒的情况，并写道，他在 2018 年“每 15 分钟”就抽一根可卡因。</p><div class="media-object scope-web
          wrap
"><div class="media-object-rich-text"><h4>分享你的意见</h4><p><em>您认为此案最有趣的是什么？加入下面的对话。</em></p></div></div><p>韦斯表示，亨特·拜登在2017年和2018年的年收入都超过150万美元，尽管每年欠税超过10万美元，但他没有为此纳税。 《华尔街日报》此前报道称<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/prosecutors-advance-tax-probe-of-hunter-biden-11648465200?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">，他偿还了约 100 万美元</a>，而指控称他未能按时支付至少 20 万美元。在检方预计提供更多细节之前，尚不清楚造成这种明显差异的原因。</p><p>根据与枪支指控相关的法庭文件，亨特·拜登在 2018 年 10 月拥有一把柯尔特眼镜蛇 38SPL 左轮手枪，尽管他吸毒成瘾并被禁止拥有枪支。</p><p>这项调查历经两届政府历时五年，并面临许多挑战，包括调查人员之间对如何进行的分歧。到 2022 年中期，调查人员认为有足够的证据来指控亨特·拜登，但<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/hunter-biden-case-decision-paused-amid-discussions-between-defense-lawyers-and-prosecutors-11665094544?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">检察官在审查辩方证据时推迟了数月</a>。除其他问题外，检察官还纠结于他的毒瘾是否可以有效地防范潜在的刑事税务案件。</p><p>拜登总统任命司法部长梅里克·加兰（Merrick Garland）的部分原因是他承诺让该部门的调查不受政治影响。他捍卫了调查的独立性，韦斯表示，他被赋予了广泛的自由度，可以在他认为合适的情况下追查此案。</p><p>周一，司法部表示韦斯将在众议院司法委员会作证，并提供了 9 月和 10 月的可能日期，强调他应该在公开听证会上发言，而不是共和党寻求的闭门听证会。</p><p>写信给 Sadie Gurman <a href="mailto:sadie.gurman@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">(sadie.gurman@wsj.com)</a>和 Aruna Viswanatha ( <a href="mailto:aruna.viswanatha@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">aruna.viswanatha@wsj.com</a> )</p><p id="correction" class="correction"><strong>更正和放大</strong><br>亨特·拜登每项罪名最高可被判处 12 个月监禁和 10 万美元罚款。本文的早期版本错误地表示，拜登每项罪名均面临 25,000 美元的罚款。 （7月26日更正）</p></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Wed, 26 Jul 2023 21:21:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/hunter-biden-plea-deal-in-jeopardy-ff556d70</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/hunter-biden-plea-deal-in-jeopardy-ff556d70<author><![CDATA[Sadie GurmanAruna Viswanatha]]></author><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>犯罪/法律诉讼</category><category>金融犯罪</category><category>欺诈罪</category><category>政治/国际关系</category><category>国内政治</category><category>税务欺诈</category><category>内容类型</category><category>法激活过滤器</category><category>C&amp;E 行政新闻过滤器</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category>玛丽莲·诺瑞卡</category><category>凯文·麦卡锡</category><category>查克·舒默</category><category>詹姆斯·科默</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>犯罪</category><category>合法举动</category><category>金融犯罪</category><category>欺诈罪</category><category>政治</category><category>国际关系</category><category>国内政治</category><category>税务欺诈</category><category>内容类型</category><category>法蒂瓦过滤器</category><category>C&amp;E 行政新闻过滤器</category></item><item><title><![CDATA[Federal Reserve Raises Interest Rates to 22-Year High]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div>官员们放慢了今年的增长步伐，但不确定他们是否已完全解决通货膨胀问题<!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001086188"><div class="is-lead-inset"><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><div class="media-object-video"><div class="wsj-media-summary clearfix"><div class="strap-container"><h4 class="strap" itemprop="description"></h4></div></div><iframe width="400" height="225" src="https://video-api.wsj.com/api-video/player/v3/iframe.html?guid=7E0252B4-152F-44EE-9C61-910343546CB6&amp;height=225&amp;width=400&amp;plid=video_amp&amp;chainVideos=true&amp;parentUrl=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.wsj.com%2Famp%2Farticles%2Ffederal-reserve-raises-interest-rates-to-22-year-high-3c3e499c&amp;a=a" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe><p class="imageCaption">观看美联储主席杰罗姆·鲍威尔的新闻发布会。<span class="imageCredit">
        
        
        </span></p></div></div></div></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001086188"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline"> <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/nick-timiraos" itemprop="url" rel="author">尼克·蒂米罗斯</a></span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1">更新于 2023 年 7 月 26 日下午 4:04（美国东部时间） </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/federal-reserve-raises-interest-rates-to-22-year-high-3c3e499c"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><p>华盛顿——美联储周三恢复加息，加息幅度为 25 个百分点，这将使利率升至<a href="https://www.wsj.com/livecoverage/fed-meeting-interest-rate-decision-today-july-2023?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none" rel="noreferrer noopener">22 年来的最高点</a>。</p><p>由于官员们争论是否采取了足够的措施来对抗通胀，上个月一致决定将基准联邦基金利率提高至 5.25% 至 5.5% 的区间，结束了加息<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/fed-holds-rates-steady-but-expects-more-increases-b1be87f2?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">的短暂停顿</a>。这是自 2022 年 3 月以来第 11 次加息，当时利率从接近于零的水平上调。</p><p>美联储<a href="https://www.federalreserve.gov/monetarypolicy/files/monetary20230726a1.pdf" target="_blank" class="icon none" rel="noopener">对其会后声明</a>进行了最小程度的修改，没有就其未来的政策计划提供新的指导。</p><p>在会后的新闻发布会上，美联储主席鲍威尔不排除在央行下次会议上再次加息的可能性，但他强调了央行已经做了多少工作，以及货币政策冷却通胀所需的时间。 </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          wrap
"><div class="media-object-rich-text"><h4>更多关于美联储的信息</h4><ul class="articleList"><li><a href="https://www.federalreserve.gov/monetarypolicy/files/monetary20230726a1.pdf" target="_blank" class="icon none" rel="noopener">美联储货币政策声明</a></li><li><a href="https://www.wsj.com/livecoverage/fed-meeting-interest-rate-decision-today-july-2023?mod=article_relatedinline" target="_blank" class="icon none" rel="noreferrer noopener">决策后股市动摇</a></li></ul></div></div><p>他说：“当我们让这一切展开时，我们可以保持一点耐心，同时也保持坚决的态度。” “我们认为，当然，我们需要在一段时间内将政策维持在限制性水平，如果我们认为合适，我们将准备进一步加息。”</p><p> <a href="https://www.wsj.com/livecoverage/fed-meeting-interest-rate-decision-today-july-2023" target="_blank" class="icon none" rel="noreferrer noopener"><br></a>美联储决定后， <a href="https://www.wsj.com/livecoverage/fed-meeting-interest-rate-decision-today-july-2023" target="_blank" class="icon none" rel="noreferrer noopener">市场涨跌互现</a>。</p><p>经济增长可能过于强劲，鲍威尔<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/markets-appear-convinced-the-fed-can-pull-off-a-soft-landing-700a40dd?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none" rel="noreferrer noopener">无法像许多投资者预期的那样</a><a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/investors-can-read-the-feds-poker-face-a1934d25?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none" rel="noreferrer noopener">暗示周三的加息将是当前紧缩周期的最后一次</a>。与此同时，近期通胀放缓可能会减轻央行官员继续加息的压力。</p><p>在六月份的上一次会议上，官员们维持利率稳定，但预计今年还会加息两次。美联储官员计划今年再召开三次会议，下一次会议将于 9 月举行。</p><p>通货膨胀已从去年夏天创下的<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/us-inflation-june-2022-consumer-price-index-11657664129" target="_blank" class="icon none">40 年来的高</a>点回落，6 月份消费者价格指数同比上涨 3%。这远低于 2022 年 6 月 9.1% 的峰值，当时汽油价格达到<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/gasoline-prices-reach-5-a-gallon-nationwide-for-the-first-time-11654910506" target="_blank" class="icon none">每加仑 5 美元的创纪录平均水平。</a> </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><div class="media-object-video"><div class="wsj-media-summary clearfix"><div class="strap-container"><h4 class="strap" itemprop="description"></h4></div></div><iframe width="400" height="225" src="https://video-api.wsj.com/api-video/player/v3/iframe.html?guid=DE0B91C0-D4B9-4619-AFE8-7EA4E62BC84B&amp;height=225&amp;width=400&amp;plid=video_amp&amp;chainVideos=true&amp;parentUrl=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.wsj.com%2Famp%2Farticles%2Ffederal-reserve-raises-interest-rates-to-22-year-high-3c3e499c&amp;a=a" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe><p class="imageCaption"> The Federal Reserve is central to the US economy today, but its power has been built over decades. Its decisions can lower inflation or spark a recession. WSJ explains how the Fed was formed and the role it plays. Photo illustration: Annie Zhao<span class="imageCredit">
        
        
        </span></p></div></div><p>Fed officials have been concerned that underlying price pressures may prove more persistent as a tight labor market allows workers to bargain for higher pay, <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/last-mile-of-the-inflation-fight-will-be-the-hardest-86bcebb1?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">making it harder</a> to get inflation down further.</p><p> Core prices, which exclude volatile food and energy categories, posted the smallest monthly gain in more than two years in the June CPI. Still, the core CPI rose 4.8% in June from a year earlier. Until last year, the core CPI hadn&#39;t registered such increases since the early 1990s.</p><p> Fed officials are focused on core inflation because they see it as a better predictor of future inflation than the overall inflation rate.</p><p> The Fed seeks to keep inflation at 2% over time, as measured by its preferred gauge, the personal-consumption expenditures price index. The Fed fights inflation by slowing the economy through raising rates, which causes tighter financial conditions such as higher borrowing costs, lower stock prices and a stronger dollar. </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          wrap
"><img width="600" height="700" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-824356?width=600" alt="不明确的" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><p> The Fed boosted interest rates aggressively in 2022 and then slowed the pace at the end of the year. Holding rates steady in June offered a way to further dial down the pace of increases and study the effects of those rapid moves, particularly after fears <a href="https://www.wsj.com/livecoverage/stock-market-today-dow-jones-05-08-2023/card/banking-stress-a-top-risk-to-u-s-economy-fed-survey-says-tan3K36YS98VljIazfHP?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">&nbsp;</a> that <a href="https://www.wsj.com/livecoverage/stock-market-today-dow-jones-05-08-2023/card/banking-stress-a-top-risk-to-u-s-economy-fed-survey-says-tan3K36YS98VljIazfHP?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">banking stress</a> this spring might further constrain credit, <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/jerome-powell-says-bank-failures-underscore-need-for-stronger-regulation-supervision-8f386569?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">Powell said last month</a> .</p><p> Officials had signaled disagreement in recent months over how quickly to keep raising rates. While all 11 voting members of the policy-setting Federal Open Market Committee agreed to last month&#39;s decision to hold rates steady, some of the 18 voting and nonvoting officials would have supported a rate rise at the June meeting, according to a <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/fed-officials-supported-raising-rates-after-june-pause-7b525544?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">written account of the meeting</a> released earlier this month.</p><p> Fed officials meet eight times a year, or roughly twice each quarter. While Powell said last month he wouldn&#39;t rule out raising rates at consecutive policy meetings, he said moving rates up at a slower, quarterly pace could be expected to continue if the economy evolves in line with current expectations.</p><p> A handful of Fed officials, however, have suggested they might prefer to raise rates again at the central bank&#39;s September meeting.</p><p> Fed officials in June raised their projections for interest rates in part because they anticipated less progress on inflation. If inflation continues to cool, that development would raise questions over whether another rate rise later this year will be needed.</p><div class="media-object scope-web
          wrap
"><div class="media-object-rich-text"><h4>分享你的意见</h4><p><em>How do you think the Fed should act next?加入下面的对话。</em></p></div></div><p> Officials who think the impact of the Fed&#39;s rate increases has yet to take full effect are more likely to favor waiting until November or December to decide whether a second interest-rate increase will be appropriate.</p><p> If economic activity slows more by then, officials could decide not to raise rates again and move to a new phase of their tightening campaign—one in which they hold rates steady as inflation slows. That would lead inflation-adjusted, or real, rates to rise higher.</p><p> “For this last part of the tightening cycle, it makes sense to stretch it out over time. They are fine-tuning. They don&#39;t know the exact destination. It makes sense to do that slowly,” said Angel Ubide, head of economic research for global fixed income at Citadel, a hedge-fund firm. </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="466" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-823209?width=700&amp;height=466" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> Federal Reserve Chair Jerome Powell didn&#39;t rule out another rate rise at the central bank&#39;s next meeting.</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: Drew Angerer/Getty Images</p></figcaption></figure></div><p> Energy and commodity prices have been responsible for <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/after-global-energy-shock-price-collapse-provides-unexpected-economic-boon-8c2b6660?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">much of the decline</a> in inflation over the past year. A recent upturn in some of those prices could underscore why officials will want to be cautious about assuming further declines in inflation, said Eric Rosengren, who served as Boston Fed president from 2007 to 2021.</p><p> A slowdown in core inflation over the coming months could create a new conundrum for the Fed if officials see reasons to think the improvement will be short lived—for example, because wage growth stays firm. “This is the old, &#39;Be careful what you wish for,&#39;” said Richard Clarida, who served as Powell&#39;s second-in-command from 2018 until January 2022.<br><br> Economists have debated over the past year whether slowing labor demand will require joblessness to rise or whether that can happen as companies reduce vacancies but not head count.</p><p> “A lot of the debate on the labor market is beside the point,” Clarida said. “If I was still over there, what I would worry about is the following: If we don&#39;t get a deceleration in wages and we don&#39;t get a pickup in productivity, then we&#39;re not going to hit our inflation target.”</p><p> Write to Nick Timiraos at <a href="mailto:Nick.Timiraos@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">Nick.Timiraos@wsj.com</a></p></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Wed, 26 Jul 2023 20:04:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/federal-reserve-raises-interest-rates-to-22-year-high-3c3e499c</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/federal-reserve-raises-interest-rates-to-22-year-high-3c3e499c<author><![CDATA[Nick Timiraos]]></author><category> gfx-contrib</category><category>华尔街日报华盛顿</category><category>通货膨胀</category><category>经济表现/指标</category><category>通货膨胀数字/价格指数</category><category>货币政策</category><category>利率</category><category>经济新闻</category><category>Inflation</category><category> SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category> Jerome Powell</category><category>经济表现</category><category>指标</category><category>通货膨胀数字</category><category>价格指数</category><category>货币政策</category><category>利率</category><category>经济新闻</category></item><item><title><![CDATA[Kevin Spacey Found Not Guilty of Sexual Offenses by U.K. Court]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div> Verdict follows a series of sexual misconduct trials for the &#39;House of Cards&#39; star <!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001085963"><div class="is-lead-inset"><div class="media-object scope-
          header
"><div class="media-object-video"><div class="wsj-media-summary clearfix"><div class="strap-container"><h4 class="strap" itemprop="description"></h4></div></div><iframe width="400" height="225" src="https://video-api.wsj.com/api-video/player/v3/iframe.html?guid=77ADAA02-5775-4A70-8B91-9DC9A54280AD&amp;height=225&amp;width=400&amp;plid=video_amp&amp;chainVideos=true&amp;parentUrl=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.wsj.com%2Famp%2Farticles%2Fkevin-spacey-found-not-guilty-of-sexual-offenses-by-u-k-court-29c943cc&amp;a=a" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe><p class="imageCaption"> Actor Kevin Spacey was found not guilty of sexual assault against four men by a UK court. Spacey was cleared of all the allegations against him involving the British men between 2001 and 2013, according to a court official. Photo: Andy Rain/Shutterstock<span class="imageCredit">
        
        
        </span></p></div></div></div></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001085963"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline"> By <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/humza-jilani" itemprop="url" rel="author">Humza Jilani</a></span> and <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/jennifer-calfas" itemprop="url" rel="author">Jennifer Calfas</a></span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1"> Updated July 26, 2023 11:43 am ET </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/kevin-spacey-found-not-guilty-of-sexual-offenses-by-u-k-court-29c943cc"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><p> LONDON—Actor Kevin Spacey was found not guilty of sexual assault against four men by a UK court, closing out <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/kevin-spacey-pleads-not-guilty-to-u-k-sexual-assault-charges-11673635720?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">a series of sexual misconduct trials</a> that have dogged the two-time Oscar winner for years.</p><p> Spacey was cleared by a jury of all the allegations against him involving the British men between 2001 and 2013, according to an official at Southwark Crown Court.</p><p> In a statement outside the court, Spacey said that he was humbled by the verdict.</p><p> “There&#39;s a lot for me to process after what has just happened today. But I would like to say that I&#39;m enormously grateful to the jury for having taken the time to examine all of the evidence and all of the facts, carefully, before they reached their decision,” Spacey said.</p><p> The period in question covered his time as artistic director of the Old Vic, a 200-year-old London theater, between 2003 and 2015.</p><p> Spacey, 63, had pleaded not guilty to all charges, ranging from indecent assault and sexual assault to causing a person to engage in penetrative sexual activity, which carries a maximum penalty of life in prison.</p><p> The verdict brings to an end a closely followed four-week trial, in which both sides focused heavily on Spacey&#39;s star power and name recognition. Spacey&#39;s lawyer depicted the actor as the victim of a trial by social media. Christine Agnew, the lead prosecutor, argued that the actor had abused his celebrity status to prey on young men. </p><div class="media-object scope-
          header
"><figure class="media-object-image img-header"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="860" height="573" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-823091?width=860&amp;height=573" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> Actor Kevin Spacey outside a UK court this week.</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: PETER CZIBORRA/REUTERS</p></figcaption></figure></div><p> The trial featured testimony from singer Elton John and his husband, David Furnish. One of the accusers alleged that Spacey had assaulted him on the way to one of the couple&#39;s white-tie galas in 2004 or 2005. John and Furnish said via video link that Spacey hadn&#39;t attended such an event during those years, the Associated Press reported.</p><p> Wednesday&#39;s verdict closes years of legal entanglements in which Spacey has faced multiple accusations of sexual misconduct in the US and the UK</p><p> In the UK, Spacey originally <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/kevin-spacey-pleads-not-guilty-to-u-k-sexual-assault-charges-11657816622?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">faced four counts of sexual assault</a> and one count of “causing a person to engage in penetrative sexual activity without consent.” Those incidents were alleged to have taken place in London in 2005 and 2008, and in Gloucestershire in 2013, with victims who are now in their 30s and 40s.</p><p> British prosecutors <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/kevin-spacey-pleads-not-guilty-to-u-k-sexual-assault-charges-11673635720?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">brought seven additional charges</a> against Spacey last year following an investigation by London&#39;s Metropolitan Police Service. Those charges included three counts of sexual assault, three counts of indecent assault and one count of causing a person to engage in sexual activity related to alleged assaults on a man between 2001 and 2004. Prosecutors didn&#39;t detail the alleged incidents nor name the man.</p><p> He was cleared of charges by a US court last year.</p><p> Spacey, who won Oscars for his roles in “The Usual Suspects” and “American Beauty,” was fired in 2017 from a starring role in</p> <a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/NFLX" class="">Netflix</a> <span class="company-name-type">&#39;s</span> “House of Cards,” after actor Anthony Rapp accused him of making a sexual advance in 1986 when Rapp was 14 and Spacey was an adult.<p></p><p> In New York, a federal jury found Spacey not liable in a battery claim brought by Rapp after <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/kevin-spacey-found-not-liable-in-civil-sexual-misconduct-case-brought-by-rent-star-anthony-rapp-11666297697?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">a two-week civil trial</a> . The 11-person jury found Rapp, who starred in “Star Trek:Discovery,” didn&#39;t prove by a preponderance of evidence that Spacey “touched a sexual or intimate part or parts of Mr. Rapp.”</p><p> <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/prosecutors-drop-case-against-kevin-spacey-11563397024?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">State prosecutors in Massachusetts in 2019</a> dropped a separate case against Spacey in which he was accused of groping a young man at a Nantucket bar. Spacey had denied the allegations and pleaded not guilty.</p><p> In an interview with a German newspaper before the UK proceedings began, Spacey insisted that he would return to acting after the trial.</p><p> “There are people right now who are ready to hire me the moment I am cleared of these charges,” ZeitMagazin quoted him as saying.</p><p> Write to Humza Jilani at <a href="mailto:humza.jilani@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">humza.jilani@wsj.com</a> and Jennifer Calfas at <a href="mailto:jennifer.calfas@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">jennifer.calfas@wsj.com</a></p></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Wed, 26 Jul 2023 15:43:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/kevin-spacey-found-not-guilty-of-sexual-offenses-by-uk-court-29c943cc</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/kevin-spacey-found-not-guilty-of-sexual-offenses-by-uk-court-29c943cc<author><![CDATA[Humza JilaniJennifer Calfas]]></author><category>华尔街日报</category><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>Celebrities</category><category>犯罪/法律诉讼</category><category>生活/生活方式</category><category>Sex Crimes</category><category> SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>celebrities</category><category>犯罪</category><category>合法举动</category><category>活的</category><category>生活方式</category><category>sex crimes </category></item><item><title><![CDATA[Replaced, Then Erased: Mystery Deepens Around China’s Former Foreign Minister]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div>外交部网站上几乎所有提及秦刚担任部长的内容都被删除，加剧了猜测<!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001085354"><div class="is-lead-inset"><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><div class="media-object-video"><div class="wsj-media-summary clearfix"><div class="strap-container"><h4 class="strap" itemprop="description"></h4></div></div><iframe width="400" height="225" src="https://video-api.wsj.com/api-video/player/v3/iframe.html?guid=9F7AF9B6-88BC-4AB6-B4C8-E0CF0C68E116&amp;height=225&amp;width=400&amp;plid=video_amp&amp;chainVideos=true&amp;parentUrl=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.wsj.com%2Famp%2Farticles%2Freplaced-then-erased-mystery-deepens-around-chinas-former-foreign-minister-9117007a&amp;a=a" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe><p class="imageCaption">北京在周二的紧急会议上重新任命最高外交官王毅接替秦刚担任外交部长，但没有提及秦刚神秘缺席的问题。中国领导人习近平七个月前亲自挑选了秦国。照片：Florence Lo/Pool 路透社/美联社<span class="imageCredit">
        
        
        </span></p></div></div></div></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001085354"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline">作者： <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/wenxin-fan" itemprop="url" rel="author">范文欣</a></span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1">Updated July 26, 2023 11:04 am ET </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/replaced-then-erased-mystery-deepens-around-chinas-former-foreign-minister-9117007a"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><p>香港——中国前外交部长在从公众视野中失踪一个多月后，于周二被接替，现在正在从外交部网站的部分内容中消失——这种删除加剧了人们对他遭遇的好奇心。</p><p>当局没有说明为何<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/china-foreign-minister-qin-gang-replaced-63660fad?mod=world_lead_pos5&amp;mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">决定免去</a>秦刚的职务，该职务目前已由他的前任王毅填补——至少是暂时的。外交部此前曾援引秦缺席的<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/china-tries-to-reassure-u-s-amid-speculation-around-missing-foreign-minister-82697971?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">健康原因，但未具体说明原因</a>。</p><p>自从用王取代他以来，外交部已经从其官方网站上删除了几乎所有提及秦担任外交部长的内容。同样，在流行的社交媒体平台<a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/WB" class="">微博</a>上<span class="company-name-type">，</span>有关秦最近担任职务的许多内容也从该部门的微博账户中消失了。</p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          wrap
"></div><p> During the Mao Zedong era, the Communist Party was known to excise senior officials from photos and other official records, typically after they fell out of favor and were purged. Such high-level erasures have been much rarer in the decades since and may never have been carried out so conspicuously.</p><p>这些变化引起了<a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/WB" class="company-name">微博</a>和中国互联网其他角落的关注，引发了对秦命运的热烈猜测。</p><p> “秦刚不是当过外交部长吗？”一位中国律师在微博上写道。 “网站处理此事的方式不合适。” </p><div class="media-object scope-
          header
"><figure class="media-object-image img-header"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="860" height="573" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-823935?width=860&amp;height=573" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> Qin Gang, shown in Beijing in May, has been missing from public view for more than a month.</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: Thomas Peter/Reuters</p></figcaption></figure></div><p> The 57-year-old served less than seven months as Chinese leader Xi Jinping&#39;s handpicked foreign minister following <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/china-promotes-u-s-ambassador-to-foreign-minister-11672409545?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">an unusually rapid rise</a> through the foreign-service ranks.政治分析人士表示，秦的网上删除削弱了他因严重健康问题而被取代的观点。</p><p> “Even if health issues had necessitated Qin&#39;s removal as foreign minister, there is no reason this would lead to the deletion of the past record of his meetings within the MFA site,” wrote David Bandurski, director of the China Media Project, a <a href="https://chinamediaproject.org/2023/07/26/chinas-foreign-minister-is-removed-and-erased/" target="_blank" class="icon none" rel="noopener">US-based research group</a> .</p><p> Bombarded by questions from reporters about Qin&#39;s status at a regular press briefing on Wednesday, Foreign Ministry spokeswoman <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/replaced-then-erased-mystery-deepens-around-chinas-former-foreign-minister-9117007a#phrase-person?ref=PERSON%7CNing%2C%20Mao;onlineSignificance=passing-mention" class="icon none">Mao Ning</a> said she had no new information to provide. All of the reporters&#39; questions about Qin and Mao&#39;s responses to them were omitted from the transcript of the press briefing posted on the ministry&#39;s website.</p><p> The drama surrounding Qin comes at <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/u-s-and-china-see-fragile-opportunity-to-repair-ties-8ad7ddff?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">a delicate time</a> for both Beijing and Washington, as the two powers have only recently re-established high-level communication at a time of soaring tensions.政治分析人士表示，69岁的中共最高外交事务专家王岐山很可能被任命为临时替代者，为习近平和其他高级官员寻找更持久的解决方案争取时间。</p><p>美国国务卿安东尼·布林肯在访问太平洋岛国汤加时表示，他祝愿秦国一切顺利，并承诺将与王毅多次会面。</p><p> “我认识王毅也有十多年了，”布林肯说。 “我希望能够和他一起很好地合作，就像我们过去一样。”</p><p> Political analysts said Qin&#39;s replacement was unlikely to derail diplomacy between the US and China in the long run because Xi sets foreign policy, though it serves to highlight the increasing <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/china-locks-information-on-the-country-inside-a-black-box-9c039928?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">opacity of China&#39;s political system</a> .</p><p>周三在外交部网站上搜索秦的中文或英文名字没有结果。该网站的一份声明中，秦继续被列为外交部长，该声明称他代表中国于三月份与洪都拉斯建交。与已被删除的数百条其他声明不同，他的名字没有出现在洪都拉斯项目的标题中。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="466" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-824129?width=700&amp;height=466" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> Secretary of State Antony Blinken met with then-Foreign Minister Qin Gang in Beijing on June 18, days before he was last seen in public.</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: Leah Millis/Reuters</p></figcaption></figure></div><p> Searches for Qin&#39;s name through the ministry&#39;s official accounts on the popular app <a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/TCEHY" class="company-name">WeChat</a></p> still produced results from his time as foreign minister.描述秦以前担任副部长和驻美国大使的新闻仍然保留在外交部网站上。<p></p><p>官方媒体关于秦被免职的报道没有提到他作为国务委员的角色有任何变化，国务委员是中国内阁的高级政府职位。截至周三下午，内阁网站已更新，删除了对他部长职务的提及，但继续列出了他的其他头衔，包括作为共产党精英中央委员会成员的头衔。</p><p>中国的互联网审查机构对秦采取了选择性的方法。周三，微博将搜索结果隐藏在一些与他被删除相关的主题标签下，以及《寻秦记》的主题标签下，这是一部以中国古代秦朝为背景的奇幻电视剧。</p><p>但除此之外，用户还有空间继续猜测他失踪的原因，包括婚外情的可能性。</p><p> “这当然不是一次正常的工作调动，”一位微博用户写道，并对中国社交媒体上似乎无处不在的婚外情谣言表示认可。该帖子获得了超过 10,000 个赞。</p><p>写信给范文欣： <a href="mailto:wenxin.fan@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">wenxin.fan@wsj.com</a> </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          inline
"><iframe width="300" height="300" src="https://graphics.wsj.com/dynamic-inset-iframer/?url=https://asset.wsj.net/wsjnewsgraphics/projects/narrator/bf4d14ac-311a-4b61-9cc1-ce0772d8de02.json" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe></div></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Wed, 26 Jul 2023 15:04:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/replaced-then-erased-mystery-deepens-around-chinas-former-foreign-minister-9117007a</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/replaced-then-erased-mystery-deepens-around-chinas-former-foreign-minister-9117007a<author><![CDATA[Wenxin Fan]]></author><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>国际关系</category><category>政治/国际关系</category><category>国内政治</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category>微博</category><category>世界银行</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>国际关系</category><category>政治</category><category>国内政治</category></item><item><title><![CDATA[How Bad Is China’s Economy? Millions of Young People Are Unemployed and Disillusioned]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div> Nation needs workers, but college graduates shun low-skill work; many opt out of job market, &#39;lying flat&#39; <figure><img src="https://images.wsj.net/im-823736/?width=1278&amp;size=1" alt="A job fair in Huai’an, China, in May." referrerpolicy="no-referrer"><figcaption> A job fair in Huai&#39;an, China, in May. He Jinghua/DDP/Zuma Press <span>He Jinghua/DDP/Zuma Press</span> </figcaption></figure><!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001083403"></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001083403"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline"> By <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/brian-spegele" itemprop="url" rel="author">Brian Spegele</a></span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1"> July 26, 2023 9:33 am ET </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/china-youth-unemployment-xi-jobs-522028c5"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          bigtophero
"></div><p> HEFEI, China—More than one in five young people in China are jobless. The government casts much of the blame on the job seekers themselves, insisting that their expectations have gotten too high.</p><p> Young people need to stiffen their spines and embrace hardship, says leader Xi Jinping, who labored in the countryside in China&#39;s Cultural Revolution. If they can&#39;t find jobs they want, they should work on factory lines or engage in poverty relief in rural China.</p><p> The government&#39;s guidance is ringing hollow with many young people. Growing up in a period of rising prosperity, they were told that China was strong, the West was declining and endless opportunities awaited them. Now, with the urban youth unemployment rate <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/chinas-economy-barely-grows-as-recovery-fades-5652a92a?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">hitting a record of 21.3% in June</a> , their employment frustrations are posing a new challenge to Xi and his vision for a more powerful China.</p><p> For the estimated 11.6 million college graduates in 2023, having heeded calls by the state to study hard, the prospect of resorting to the physical labor that many of their parents performed is distinctly unappealing.</p><p> China&#39;s State Council Information Office, which handles media inquiries for senior leaders, didn&#39;t respond to a request for comment.</p><p> In the city of Hefei, a hub of universities 250 miles west of Shanghai, 23-year-old Liu Xingyu chafes at the criticism by older people that Chinese youths are too picky.</p><p> “They&#39;re not from our generation, and they don&#39;t understand us, so their opinions don&#39;t matter much to us,” said Liu, who recently quit her first job out of college a few months after starting and joined the ranks of China&#39;s young unemployed.</p><p> Liu studied communications engineering at college because she saw it as a practical choice that would help her secure steady work. As graduation neared, the best she could find was a cellphone sales management training program at a shopping mall, earning the equivalent of $630 a month, about half the city&#39;s average income. When the company later offered her a full-time gig, she said, it wanted to cut her base salary by more than half, prompting her to quit.</p><p> The problem isn&#39;t that jobs don&#39;t exist in China. They do. With <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/chinas-population-declined-in-2022-for-first-time-in-decades-11673921036?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">its shrinking population</a> , China needs workers as much as ever. It is that China&#39;s weakened economy <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/the-problem-that-wont-go-away-in-china-high-youth-unemployment-f22e3b8c?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">isn&#39;t producing enough of the high-skill, high-wage jobs</a> that many college students have come to expect. </p><div class="media-object scope-
          bleed
"><figure class="media-object-image img-bleed"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="1260" height="840" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-823763?width=1260&amp;height=840" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: wu hao/EPA/Shutterstock </p></figcaption></figure></div><div class="media-object scope-
          bleed
"><figure class="media-object-image img-bleed"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="1260" height="840" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-823739?width=1260&amp;height=840" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> China produced an estimated 11.6 million college graduates in 2023. Graduation festivities in June at Renmin University, top, and Wuhan University, above.</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: Getty Images</p></figcaption></figure></div><p> This is especially so after Xi&#39;s targeting of the private sector in recent years with regulatory crackdowns on technology and other companies.</p><p> Disenchanted, many young people are opting out of the job market entirely, or “lying flat,” as many of them call it. Chinese media has recently featured articles about young “drifters” who live hand-to-mouth and pick up odd jobs as they roam the country.</p><p> Many of those who still want to work have soured on the private sector, with surging numbers of people sitting for the country&#39;s civil-service exam for a chance at a low-paid, but stable, role in China&#39;s bureaucracy.</p><p> The true level of China&#39;s unemployment rate for young people ages 16 to 24 may be even higher than indicated by official data. Zhang Dandan, a Peking University economist, estimated the real youth unemployment rate in March could have reached 46.5%, compared with the official figure that month of less than 20%, if the millions of people who aren&#39;t participating in the workforce also were counted. </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          wrap
"><img width="600" height="800" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-824633?width=600" alt="不明确的" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><p> For now, the mood among the young unemployed is more apathy than anger, especially with many parents pitching in to cover their living costs.</p><p> Longer term, the risk is that millions of unemployed people will lose the ambition China needs to achieve <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/china-congress-xi-jinping-us-11665753002?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">Xi&#39;s goal of rejuvenating the country</a> as a great power, and will struggle on the fringes of society as potential threats to the Communist Party.</p><p> Without stable work, many Chinese are putting off getting married and having children, worsening the country&#39;s demographic problems. Some scholars warn about the emergence of a class of “new poor” in China who live off their parents, and could destabilize society.</p><p> “Because the &#39;new poor&#39; have long been living in exclusion, oblivion and boredom, their main mental states have become irritable, antisocial and violent,” said Sun Feng, a Tsinghua University sociologist, in a recent commentary on a prominent party website. “These will be the primary factors that breed social instability.”</p><p> Asked recently about the joblessness of young people, China&#39;s Minister of Education Huai Jinpeng said Xi attached considerable importance to the issue of unemployment. Huai said that conceptions of work were changing in China, with some young people seeking more flexibility.</p><p> “But at the same time, we prefer a more positive view of employment, understanding society, dedicating youth and creating value through practice and employment,” he said.</p><p> While Xi retains widespread popular support in China, some young people&#39;s frustrations about his tight control on society and the economy burst into the open last November when street protests over the country&#39;s Covid policies erupted in Beijing, Shanghai and other cities. </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="467" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-823767?width=700&amp;height=467" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> Street protests in Beijing in November of last year.</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: Ng Han Guan/Associated Press</p></figcaption></figure></div><p> Job-market anxiety was evident in Hefei last week, where thousands of graduates flooded into a jobs fair organized by the local government. Companies advertised sought-after office roles such as in graphic design or account management. Images of Xi mingling with students flashed on a large screen overhead.</p><p> With so much competition, companies could be picky.</p><p> “Dude, you might not be the right fit,” the recruiter of a popular local restaurant chain told one young man, who then walked away.</p><p> Across town, a recruitment center that helps job seekers land factory work was practically deserted. Many young college graduates don&#39;t want to work on assembly lines, said Wu You, an employee of the recruitment center, even though such jobs can pay as much as or more than entry-level white-collar ones.</p><p> On social media, some college graduates have been posting photos of themselves lying face down in their graduation gowns to show their malaise. Others compare their situations to a well-known character from Chinese literature, Kong Yiji, a self-styled intellectual who resorts to petty theft after failing to secure work with the government.</p><p> Overall, China&#39;s official urban unemployment rate is just 5.2%. Young people are getting hit much harder for a mix of reasons tied to <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/for-many-in-china-it-feels-like-a-recession-25ce4b68?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">China&#39;s economic outlook</a> and structural issues in the country&#39;s labor market. Some of those problems have been exacerbated by government actions.</p><p> China&#39;s economy <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/chinas-economy-barely-grows-as-recovery-fades-5652a92a?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">grew just 0.8% in the second quarter</a> compared with the first three months of the year, an anemic rate that showed how the country, <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/chinas-fading-recovery-reveals-deeper-economic-struggles-31f4097b?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">hamstrung by heavy borrowing</a> and a <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/chinas-property-market-enters-troubling-new-phase-1fe3143d?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">property-market downturn</a> , is struggling to regain momentum after the pandemic. Instead of investing in projects that would create new jobs for college graduates, many companies have been focused on <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/fueled-by-long-credit-binge-chinas-economy-faces-drag-from-debt-purge-e4621859?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">paying down debt</a> . The government has cracked down on sectors that were traditionally big employers of young people, such as technology and real estate. </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          wrap
"><img width="600" height="800" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-823972?width=600" alt="不明确的" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><p> Yet higher-education enrollment has continued to expand. In the past three years, more than 28 million college graduates entered the labor market, accounting for about two-thirds of the new urban labor supply.</p><p> That has created a mismatch between the jobs young people want and the ones available. Research by the online recruitment firm Zhilian Zhaopin found that a quarter of Chinese graduates this year were seeking work in the technology space, more than double the level of the next biggest category, even though some of China&#39;s biggest tech companies <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/tencent-bytedance-implement-fresh-layoffs-amid-chinas-economic-pains-11656590596?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">have had layoffs</a> .</p><p> Meanwhile, the government has reported the greatest worker shortages in blue-collar jobs such as manufacturing and in low-paid service ones such as housekeeping, which college graduates are less willing to accept. </p><div class="media-object scope-
          bleed
"><figure class="media-object-image img-bleed"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="1260" height="840" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-823785?width=1260&amp;height=840" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> With its shrinking population, China needs workers as much as ever, but many college graduates aren&#39;t interested in assembly-line work. Employees at a factory of Chinese automaker NIO in Hefei.</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: hector retamal/Agence France-Presse/Getty Images</p></figcaption></figure></div><p> With relatively few jobs in higher paying fields, college students nearing graduation often find themselves competing against graduate students—and companies tend to hire the latter, Zhilian Zhaopin found.</p><p> For those who do land jobs, the working environments can be grueling. Chinese tech companies are famous for pushing employees 12 hours a day, six days a week. At state-owned firms, some employees must study <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/three-wise-men-xi-seeks-to-join-mao-and-deng-in-chinas-holy-scripture-1508491813?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">Xi Jinping Thought</a> alongside their day jobs.</p><p> In Hefei, two recent graduates who snagged internships at a local bank said they are required to participate in group physical exercise each day and hand over their cellphones while at work.</p><p> At the jobs fair in Hefei, recent graduate Han Jiahao said he dreamed of working as a photographer and that many other young people like him sought greater independence in their work lives.</p><p> While stable work might be better for raising a family, he said, the relative autonomy of being a photographer was appealing because it would leave him less exhausted at the end of the day.</p><p> At the jobs fair, Han said, a teacher he consulted encouraged him to find a practical job first and then consider pivoting to photography later. “University students typically prefer to be free,” Han said.</p><p> China&#39;s government has said it is working to address youth unemployment. At an April meeting, the party&#39;s Politburo called on the country to expand job opportunities for college graduates. Local governments have rolled out programs such as providing subsidies for companies that hire recent graduates and special loans to help graduates start companies.</p><p> Those efforts don&#39;t address the underlying economic weaknesses preventing many companies from hiring more people. Although Beijing last week unveiled 31 guidelines aimed at <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/beijing-rushes-to-shore-up-battered-private-economy-skepticism-abounds-80c1a23c?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">bolstering the private sector</a> , which could improve hiring, many analysts remain skeptical after seeing the tightened control of private enterprise during the first decade of Xi&#39;s leadership.</p><p> Popular government slogans, such as “get a job first, then find a career,” run counter to what many parents want for their children—a more comfortable work life than they had. </p><div class="media-object scope-
          bleed
"><figure class="media-object-image img-bleed"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="1260" height="840" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-823741?width=1260&amp;height=840" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> Graduates attended a job fair for private enterprises in Huai&#39;an in May.</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: Zhao Qirui/Cfoto/Zuma Press</p></figcaption></figure></div><p> The Chinese government&#39;s recent messaging, by contrast, extols the virtues of factory work and toiling in the countryside, and urges graduates to adopt what officials call “the correct outlook” on jobs.</p><p> “The more ambitious you are, the more down to earth you need to be,” the Communist Party&#39;s People&#39;s Daily said earlier this month.</p><p> Liu, the 23-year-old woman who landed work in cellphone sales, said she initially viewed the job as providing stability, after having dealt with the uncertainty of the pandemic for three years.</p><p> After Covid hit, Liu recalled, classes moved online, and she was largely confined by school administrators to her dorm room, with three roommates. She struggled to focus and received average grades.</p><p> When it came time to graduate, Liu landed interviews for promising jobs at a state telecommunications company and the Chinese appliance manufacturer <a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/CN/XSHE/000333" class="">Midea Group</a> <span class="company-name-type">.</span> But neither job came through.</p><p> She accepted the cellphone sales training offer as a fallback. She was relieved to have a job, but also felt that her engineering studies were going to waste.</p><p> “A lot of times I would find myself thinking, what&#39;s the point of going to college if I&#39;m going to end up doing this?” Liu said.</p><p> When the full-time job offer arrived, she balked at the base salary, which was less than half what she had been earning as a trainee. Slow sales meant that even after commissions, her total take-home pay likely would be less than she earned while in training, she said.</p><p> Dejected by the offer, Liu quit.</p><p> “It was a joy when I left that job, not having to suffer in that position,” she said.</p><p> Liu doesn&#39;t have any immediate plans to start working again. She said she planned to buy books to study for the civil-service exam instead.</p><p class="articleTagLine"> —Qianwei Zhang contributed to this article.</p><p> Write to Brian Spegele at <a href="mailto:Brian.Spegele@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">Brian.Spegele@wsj.com</a></p></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Wed, 26 Jul 2023 13:33:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/china-youth-unemployment-xi-jobs-522028c5</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/china-youth-unemployment-xi-jobs-522028c5<author><![CDATA[Brian Spegele]]></author><category>领导者</category><category>华尔街日报</category><category>经济表现/指标</category><category>Employment/Unemployment Figures</category><category>经济新闻</category><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>教育</category><category>General Labor Issues</category><category>大学学院</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category>经济表现</category><category>指标</category><category>employment</category><category> unemployment figures</category><category>经济新闻</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>教育</category><category>general labor issues</category><category>大学</category><category>大学</category></item><item><title><![CDATA[How Bad Is China’s Economy? Millions of Young People Are Unemployed and Disillusioned]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div> Nation needs workers, but college graduates shun low-skill work; many opt out of job market, &#39;lying flat&#39; <figure><img src="https://images.wsj.net/im-823736/?width=1278&amp;size=1" alt="A job fair in Huai’an, China, in May." referrerpolicy="no-referrer"><figcaption> A job fair in Huai&#39;an, China, in May. He Jinghua/DDP/Zuma Press <span>He Jinghua/DDP/Zuma Press</span> </figcaption></figure><!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001083403"></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001083403"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline"> By <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/brian-spegele" itemprop="url" rel="author">Brian Spegele</a></span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1"> July 26, 2023 9:33 am ET </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/china-youth-unemployment-xi-jobs-522028c5"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          bigtophero
"></div><p> HEFEI, China—More than one in five young people in China are jobless. The government casts much of the blame on the job seekers themselves, insisting that their expectations have gotten too high.</p><p> Young people need to stiffen their spines and embrace hardship, says leader Xi Jinping, who labored in the countryside in China&#39;s Cultural Revolution. If they can&#39;t find jobs they want, they should work on factory lines or engage in poverty relief in rural China.</p><p> The government&#39;s guidance is ringing hollow with many young people. Growing up in a period of rising prosperity, they were told that China was strong, the West was declining and endless opportunities awaited them. Now, with the urban youth unemployment rate <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/chinas-economy-barely-grows-as-recovery-fades-5652a92a?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">hitting a record of 21.3% in June</a> , their employment frustrations are posing a new challenge to Xi and his vision for a more powerful China.</p><p> For the estimated 11.6 million college graduates in 2023, having heeded calls by the state to study hard, the prospect of resorting to the physical labor that many of their parents performed is distinctly unappealing.</p><p> China&#39;s State Council Information Office, which handles media inquiries for senior leaders, didn&#39;t respond to a request for comment.</p><p> In the city of Hefei, a hub of universities 250 miles west of Shanghai, 23-year-old Liu Xingyu chafes at the criticism by older people that Chinese youths are too picky.</p><p> “They&#39;re not from our generation, and they don&#39;t understand us, so their opinions don&#39;t matter much to us,” said Liu, who recently quit her first job out of college a few months after starting and joined the ranks of China&#39;s young unemployed.</p><p> Liu studied communications engineering at college because she saw it as a practical choice that would help her secure steady work. As graduation neared, the best she could find was a cellphone sales management training program at a shopping mall, earning the equivalent of $630 a month, about half the city&#39;s average income. When the company later offered her a full-time gig, she said, it wanted to cut her base salary by more than half, prompting her to quit.</p><p> The problem isn&#39;t that jobs don&#39;t exist in China. They do. With <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/chinas-population-declined-in-2022-for-first-time-in-decades-11673921036?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">its shrinking population</a> , China needs workers as much as ever. It is that China&#39;s weakened economy <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/the-problem-that-wont-go-away-in-china-high-youth-unemployment-f22e3b8c?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">isn&#39;t producing enough of the high-skill, high-wage jobs</a> that many college students have come to expect. </p><div class="media-object scope-
          bleed
"><figure class="media-object-image img-bleed"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="1260" height="840" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-823763?width=1260&amp;height=840" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: wu hao/EPA/Shutterstock </p></figcaption></figure></div><div class="media-object scope-
          bleed
"><figure class="media-object-image img-bleed"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="1260" height="840" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-823739?width=1260&amp;height=840" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> China produced an estimated 11.6 million college graduates in 2023. Graduation festivities in June at Renmin University, top, and Wuhan University, above.</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: Getty Images</p></figcaption></figure></div><p> This is especially so after Xi&#39;s targeting of the private sector in recent years with regulatory crackdowns on technology and other companies.</p><p> Disenchanted, many young people are opting out of the job market entirely, or “lying flat,” as many of them call it. Chinese media has recently featured articles about young “drifters” who live hand-to-mouth and pick up odd jobs as they roam the country.</p><p> Many of those who still want to work have soured on the private sector, with surging numbers of people sitting for the country&#39;s civil-service exam for a chance at a low-paid, but stable, role in China&#39;s bureaucracy.</p><p> The true level of China&#39;s unemployment rate for young people ages 16 to 24 may be even higher than indicated by official data. Zhang Dandan, a Peking University economist, estimated the real youth unemployment rate in March could have reached 46.5%, compared with the official figure that month of less than 20%, if the millions of people who aren&#39;t participating in the workforce also were counted. </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          wrap
"><img width="600" height="800" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-824633?width=600" alt="不明确的" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><p> For now, the mood among the young unemployed is more apathy than anger, especially with many parents pitching in to cover their living costs.</p><p> Longer term, the risk is that millions of unemployed people will lose the ambition China needs to achieve <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/china-congress-xi-jinping-us-11665753002?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">Xi&#39;s goal of rejuvenating the country</a> as a great power, and will struggle on the fringes of society as potential threats to the Communist Party.</p><p> Without stable work, many Chinese are putting off getting married and having children, worsening the country&#39;s demographic problems. Some scholars warn about the emergence of a class of “new poor” in China who live off their parents, and could destabilize society.</p><p> “Because the &#39;new poor&#39; have long been living in exclusion, oblivion and boredom, their main mental states have become irritable, antisocial and violent,” said Sun Feng, a Tsinghua University sociologist, in a recent commentary on a prominent party website. “These will be the primary factors that breed social instability.”</p><p> Asked recently about the joblessness of young people, China&#39;s Minister of Education Huai Jinpeng said Xi attached considerable importance to the issue of unemployment. Huai said that conceptions of work were changing in China, with some young people seeking more flexibility.</p><p> “But at the same time, we prefer a more positive view of employment, understanding society, dedicating youth and creating value through practice and employment,” he said.</p><p> While Xi retains widespread popular support in China, some young people&#39;s frustrations about his tight control on society and the economy burst into the open last November when street protests over the country&#39;s Covid policies erupted in Beijing, Shanghai and other cities. </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="467" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-823767?width=700&amp;height=467" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> Street protests in Beijing in November of last year.</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: Ng Han Guan/Associated Press</p></figcaption></figure></div><p> Job-market anxiety was evident in Hefei last week, where thousands of graduates flooded into a jobs fair organized by the local government. Companies advertised sought-after office roles such as in graphic design or account management. Images of Xi mingling with students flashed on a large screen overhead.</p><p> With so much competition, companies could be picky.</p><p> “Dude, you might not be the right fit,” the recruiter of a popular local restaurant chain told one young man, who then walked away.</p><p> Across town, a recruitment center that helps job seekers land factory work was practically deserted. Many young college graduates don&#39;t want to work on assembly lines, said Wu You, an employee of the recruitment center, even though such jobs can pay as much as or more than entry-level white-collar ones.</p><p> On social media, some college graduates have been posting photos of themselves lying face down in their graduation gowns to show their malaise. Others compare their situations to a well-known character from Chinese literature, Kong Yiji, a self-styled intellectual who resorts to petty theft after failing to secure work with the government.</p><p> Overall, China&#39;s official urban unemployment rate is just 5.2%. Young people are getting hit much harder for a mix of reasons tied to <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/for-many-in-china-it-feels-like-a-recession-25ce4b68?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">China&#39;s economic outlook</a> and structural issues in the country&#39;s labor market. Some of those problems have been exacerbated by government actions.</p><p> China&#39;s economy <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/chinas-economy-barely-grows-as-recovery-fades-5652a92a?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">grew just 0.8% in the second quarter</a> compared with the first three months of the year, an anemic rate that showed how the country, <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/chinas-fading-recovery-reveals-deeper-economic-struggles-31f4097b?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">hamstrung by heavy borrowing</a> and a <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/chinas-property-market-enters-troubling-new-phase-1fe3143d?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">property-market downturn</a> , is struggling to regain momentum after the pandemic. Instead of investing in projects that would create new jobs for college graduates, many companies have been focused on <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/fueled-by-long-credit-binge-chinas-economy-faces-drag-from-debt-purge-e4621859?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">paying down debt</a> . The government has cracked down on sectors that were traditionally big employers of young people, such as technology and real estate. </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          wrap
"><img width="600" height="800" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-823972?width=600" alt="不明确的" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><p> Yet higher-education enrollment has continued to expand. In the past three years, more than 28 million college graduates entered the labor market, accounting for about two-thirds of the new urban labor supply.</p><p> That has created a mismatch between the jobs young people want and the ones available. Research by the online recruitment firm Zhilian Zhaopin found that a quarter of Chinese graduates this year were seeking work in the technology space, more than double the level of the next biggest category, even though some of China&#39;s biggest tech companies <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/tencent-bytedance-implement-fresh-layoffs-amid-chinas-economic-pains-11656590596?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">have had layoffs</a> .</p><p> Meanwhile, the government has reported the greatest worker shortages in blue-collar jobs such as manufacturing and in low-paid service ones such as housekeeping, which college graduates are less willing to accept. </p><div class="media-object scope-
          bleed
"><figure class="media-object-image img-bleed"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="1260" height="840" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-823785?width=1260&amp;height=840" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> With its shrinking population, China needs workers as much as ever, but many college graduates aren&#39;t interested in assembly-line work. Employees at a factory of Chinese automaker NIO in Hefei.</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: hector retamal/Agence France-Presse/Getty Images</p></figcaption></figure></div><p> With relatively few jobs in higher paying fields, college students nearing graduation often find themselves competing against graduate students—and companies tend to hire the latter, Zhilian Zhaopin found.</p><p> For those who do land jobs, the working environments can be grueling. Chinese tech companies are famous for pushing employees 12 hours a day, six days a week. At state-owned firms, some employees must study <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/three-wise-men-xi-seeks-to-join-mao-and-deng-in-chinas-holy-scripture-1508491813?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">Xi Jinping Thought</a> alongside their day jobs.</p><p> In Hefei, two recent graduates who snagged internships at a local bank said they are required to participate in group physical exercise each day and hand over their cellphones while at work.</p><p> At the jobs fair in Hefei, recent graduate Han Jiahao said he dreamed of working as a photographer and that many other young people like him sought greater independence in their work lives.</p><p> While stable work might be better for raising a family, he said, the relative autonomy of being a photographer was appealing because it would leave him less exhausted at the end of the day.</p><p> At the jobs fair, Han said, a teacher he consulted encouraged him to find a practical job first and then consider pivoting to photography later. “University students typically prefer to be free,” Han said.</p><p> China&#39;s government has said it is working to address youth unemployment. At an April meeting, the party&#39;s Politburo called on the country to expand job opportunities for college graduates. Local governments have rolled out programs such as providing subsidies for companies that hire recent graduates and special loans to help graduates start companies.</p><p> Those efforts don&#39;t address the underlying economic weaknesses preventing many companies from hiring more people. Although Beijing last week unveiled 31 guidelines aimed at <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/beijing-rushes-to-shore-up-battered-private-economy-skepticism-abounds-80c1a23c?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">bolstering the private sector</a> , which could improve hiring, many analysts remain skeptical after seeing the tightened control of private enterprise during the first decade of Xi&#39;s leadership.</p><p> Popular government slogans, such as “get a job first, then find a career,” run counter to what many parents want for their children—a more comfortable work life than they had. </p><div class="media-object scope-
          bleed
"><figure class="media-object-image img-bleed"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="1260" height="840" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-823741?width=1260&amp;height=840" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> Graduates attended a job fair for private enterprises in Huai&#39;an in May.</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: Zhao Qirui/Cfoto/Zuma Press</p></figcaption></figure></div><p> The Chinese government&#39;s recent messaging, by contrast, extols the virtues of factory work and toiling in the countryside, and urges graduates to adopt what officials call “the correct outlook” on jobs.</p><p> “The more ambitious you are, the more down to earth you need to be,” the Communist Party&#39;s People&#39;s Daily said earlier this month.</p><p> Liu, the 23-year-old woman who landed work in cellphone sales, said she initially viewed the job as providing stability, after having dealt with the uncertainty of the pandemic for three years.</p><p> After Covid hit, Liu recalled, classes moved online, and she was largely confined by school administrators to her dorm room, with three roommates. She struggled to focus and received average grades.</p><p> When it came time to graduate, Liu landed interviews for promising jobs at a state telecommunications company and the Chinese appliance manufacturer <a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/CN/XSHE/000333" class="">Midea Group</a> <span class="company-name-type">.</span> But neither job came through.</p><p> She accepted the cellphone sales training offer as a fallback. She was relieved to have a job, but also felt that her engineering studies were going to waste.</p><p> “A lot of times I would find myself thinking, what&#39;s the point of going to college if I&#39;m going to end up doing this?” Liu said.</p><p> When the full-time job offer arrived, she balked at the base salary, which was less than half what she had been earning as a trainee. Slow sales meant that even after commissions, her total take-home pay likely would be less than she earned while in training, she said.</p><p> Dejected by the offer, Liu quit.</p><p> “It was a joy when I left that job, not having to suffer in that position,” she said.</p><p> Liu doesn&#39;t have any immediate plans to start working again. She said she planned to buy books to study for the civil-service exam instead.</p><p class="articleTagLine"> —Qianwei Zhang contributed to this article.</p><p> Write to Brian Spegele at <a href="mailto:Brian.Spegele@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">Brian.Spegele@wsj.com</a></p></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Wed, 26 Jul 2023 13:33:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/china-youth-unemployment-xi-jobs-522028c5</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/china-youth-unemployment-xi-jobs-522028c5<author><![CDATA[Brian Spegele]]></author><category>领导者</category><category>华尔街日报</category><category>经济表现/指标</category><category>Employment/Unemployment Figures</category><category>经济新闻</category><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>教育</category><category>General Labor Issues</category><category>大学学院</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category>经济表现</category><category>指标</category><category>employment</category><category> unemployment figures</category><category>经济新闻</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>教育</category><category>general labor issues</category><category>大学</category><category>大学</category></item><item><title><![CDATA[What’s Happening in Israel? Protests and Strikes Over Netanyahu’s Judicial Overhaul]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div>以色列领导人的举动导致国家分裂，引发大规模抗议，以下是您需要了解的情况<figure><img src="https://images.wsj.net/im-823207/?width=1278&amp;size=1" alt="抗议者参加特拉维夫的示威活动。" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"><figcaption>抗议者参加特拉维夫的示威活动。伊利亚·叶菲莫维奇/DPA/祖玛出版社<span>伊利亚·叶菲莫维奇/DPA/祖玛出版社</span></figcaption></figure><!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0000724990"></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0000724990"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline"> <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/dov-lieber" itemprop="url" rel="author">多夫·利伯</a></span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1">Updated July 26, 2023 9:00 am ET </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/israel-protests-judicial-overhaul-netanyahu-7e264a71"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          bigtophero
"></div><p>耶路撒冷——近几个月来，数十万以色列人走上全国街头示威，反对总理本杰明·内塔尼亚胡政府计划的<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/israeli-doctors-go-on-strike-to-protest-netanyahus-judicial-overhaul-463530e7?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">司法改革</a>。</p><p> 7 月 24 日，执政联盟推动以色列议会获得通过，这是该联盟希望通过的一系列<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/israel-netanyahu-government-judicial-overhaul-protests-862dffd3?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">限制法院系统权力的</a>法律中的第一部。在达成妥协的谈判破裂后，该法案在没有任何反对派支持的情况下获得通过。反对派议员走出房间，抵制投票。</p><p>内塔尼亚胡是该国任职时间最长的总理，目前已进入第六个任期，在他的政府于三月份首次尝试通过另一套不同的法案后，内塔尼亚胡使司法立法从失败中恢复过来。在大规模抗议和大罢工导致国家瘫痪后，他<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/strike-called-flights-grounded-in-israel-over-netanyahus-judicial-overhaul-plan-e8c95930?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none" rel="noreferrer noopener">推迟了这项努力</a>，但他在六月份表示，他将以修改后的形式通过这项改革。</p><p>该法律的通过标志着以色列社会的一个关键时刻，可能与该国最高法院摊牌，而该法律旨在遏制该机构的权力。对于数千名表示将退出的<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/israels-judicial-overhaul-raises-security-concerns-as-reservists-refuse-to-serve-5d68bfff?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">预备役军人</a>，以及威胁要大规模停工的商界、工会领导人和医疗专业人员来说，这是一个决定性的时刻。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          bleed
"><div class="media-object-video"><div class="wsj-media-summary clearfix"><div class="strap-container"><h4 class="strap" itemprop="description"></h4></div></div><iframe width="400" height="225" src="https://video-api.wsj.com/api-video/player/v3/iframe.html?guid=B58B7540-4CF9-464C-A04F-C0E71926FD01&amp;height=225&amp;width=400&amp;plid=video_amp&amp;chainVideos=true&amp;parentUrl=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.wsj.com%2Famp%2Farticles%2Fisrael-protests-judicial-overhaul-netanyahu-7e264a71&amp;a=a" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe><p class="imageCaption">以色列医生周二举行罢工，当局在因总理本杰明·内塔尼亚胡政府进行的司法改革而发生骚乱的夜晚，强行将抗议者从道路上带走。照片：阿米尔·利维/盖蒂图片社<span class="imageCredit">
        
        
        </span></p></div></div><p>以色列最大的工会以色列总工会表示，他们正在为可能举行的总罢工做准备，一些抗议者正在敦促其采取这样的行动。然而，工会决定不在第一项法案通过后立即宣布大罢工。</p><p>第一项法案通过的第二天，以色列的医生和医务人员举行了罢工。</p><p>此次改革<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/israeli-judicial-overhaul-pits-secular-religious-communities-against-each-other-a4177c16?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none" rel="noreferrer noopener">引发了该国的分裂</a>，引发了美国等主要盟友的担忧，并在伊朗支持的真主党武装组织沿其北部边境造成的威胁日益加大的情况下，引发了对其军事准备情况的质疑。分析人士警告说，该国可能会陷入宪法危机。</p><p>这是您需要了解的内容。</p><h3>以色列民众为何抗议？</h3><p>在这个拥有 900 万人口的国家，每个周末都有多达 50 万以色列人出来抗议内塔尼亚胡<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/netanyahu-advances-overhaul-of-top-israeli-court-drawing-thousands-of-protesters-ee0287d7?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">计划的对该国司法机构的改革</a>。</p><p>示威者和该国的政治反对派表示，该计划将削弱以色列本已脆弱的制衡体系，并破坏民主和对少数群体的保护。他们还表示，此次改革将对以色列的民主性格造成致命打击。</p><p> <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/israels-right-wing-lawmakers-aim-to-remake-supreme-court-11668506325?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none" rel="noreferrer noopener">关于以色列最高法院的争论</a>部分是由于该国自建国以来法律体系的模糊性造成的。以色列没有成文宪法。相反，法院的判决基于英国普通法、不断发展的以色列先例和一系列基本法，这些法律提供了准宪法的权力。</p><p>围绕最高法院的斗争也成为以色列社会更深层次裂痕的代表。 <a href="https://www.wsj.com/story/why-israelis-are-protesting-netanyahu-governments-judicial-overhaul-0933acc5?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">抗议活动</a>使自由派、世俗的以色列人（他们将法院视为人权的保障者）与极端正统派以及宗教和政治保守派进行了对立，后者认为法院是实现其政策目标的障碍。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          bleed
"><figure class="media-object-image img-bleed"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="1260" height="839" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-823210?width=1260&amp;height=839" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">议会通过司法改革提案的第一部分后，耶路撒冷的抗议者。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：Orit Ben-Ezzer/Zuma Press</p></figcaption></figure></div><h3>这场危机的核心是哪些司法变革？</h3><p>内塔尼亚胡的 64 名议员组成的整个联盟于 7 月 24 日投票支持一项法律，该法律剥夺了最高法院撤销其认为“极其不合理”的政府决定的能力——他们认为这一概念含糊不清，并允许自由派法官推翻日益右翼选民的意愿。</p><p>这是联盟希望通过的一系列限制法院系统权力的法律中的第一部。接下来是一项法案，该法案将赋予立法者更多选择法官的权力，这一举措比周一通过的法案更具争议性。它可能会在秋季进行投票。</p><p> <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/netanyahu-revives-judicial-overhaul-stripped-of-most-controversial-piece-33160de" target="_blank" class="icon none" rel="noreferrer noopener">内塔尼亚胡六月告诉《华尔街日报》</a> ，他将放弃该计划在以色列以外地区最具争议的部分，这将赋予国家立法机构推翻最高法院裁决的权力。</p><p>所谓的“优先条款”将允许议会以 61 名议员的多数票否决最高法院有关立法的决定。这些提案还需要绝大多数法官才能推翻议会法律。批评者表示，拟议的改革实际上将结束对议会的司法审查，因为以色列历史上几乎每个议会联盟都拥有 61 个或更多席位。</p><h3>内塔尼亚胡为何推动司法改革计划？</h3><p>内塔尼亚胡三月份暂停了改革计划，并在大规模抗议后开始<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/israel-calms-after-netanyahu-suspends-judicial-overhaul-b951d2c?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none" rel="noreferrer noopener">与反对派进行妥协谈判</a>。但在六月下旬，他表示双方未能达成协议，他将继续推进自己修改后的计划。</p><p>这位长期执政的领导人历来都不是改革司法制度的倡导者，但他面临着来自其联盟成员的巨大压力，要求他通过这一改革。联盟成员被广泛认为是该国75年历史上最右翼、民族主义和宗教色彩最浓厚的人。</p><p>关于司法立法的辩论揭示了以色列社会对于犹太国家和民主国家的意义的分歧。 The state was founded and controlled in its early decades by secular socialists of largely Eastern European descent. They envisioned a culturally Jewish but socially liberal democratic state.</p><p> Over recent decades, an alliance between various segments that have come to represent the Israeli right—religious Zionists, settlers, the ultraorthodox and Jews of Middle Eastern descent—has grown in both numbers and power.内塔尼亚胡领导的利库德集团本身是世俗的，它已将这些右翼势力联合成一个政治强国。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          bleed
"><figure class="media-object-image img-bleed"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="1260" height="840" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-823214?width=1260&amp;height=840" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">以色列总理本杰明·内塔尼亚胡在耶路撒冷举行的议会会议上。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：玛雅·阿莱鲁佐/美联社</p></figcaption></figure></div><h3>下一步是什么？</h3><p>非政府组织和其他组织已提交请愿书<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/israels-supreme-court-could-strike-down-a-bill-aimed-at-limiting-its-power-but-will-it-cc17a8d7?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">，要求以色列最高法院推翻该法律</a>，这类似于宪法修正案，取消了法院推翻其认为极其不合理的政府决定的权力。</p><p> Israel&#39;s Supreme Court said on July 26 that it would hear a case challenging the constitutionality of the bill. It set a preliminary hearing, which will be heard by one justice, for September. The court could then decide to bring the case before an extended panel that could include as many as 11 justices.</p><p>最高法院从未做过这样的准宪法法律，但现在迫于公众压力却不得不这么做。</p><p>以色列国家安全部长、该国极端民族主义右翼领导人伊塔马尔·本-格维尔表示，如果法院推翻这项法律，那将是“一场未遂政变”。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          bleed
"><figure class="media-object-image img-bleed"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="1260" height="840" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-823222?width=1260&amp;height=840" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">以色列预备役军人在特拉维夫签署一份声明。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：Matan Golan/SOPA/Zuma Press</p></figcaption></figure></div><h3>这是否会影响以色列与美国的关系？</h3><p>尽管<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/u-s-ambassador-warned-israel-against-going-off-the-rails-with-judicial-overhaul-d612fffa?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">拜登政府一再发出警告</a>，内塔尼亚胡仍继续推进司法改革，其中包括在投票前几个小时，拜登总统发表公开声明，称该措施“正在变得更加分裂，而不是减少”。</p><p>在这些措施通过后，拜登政府官员很快坚称，正如白宫新闻秘书卡琳·让-皮埃尔所说，美以关系仍然“坚如磐石”。她没有直接回答有关是否会对以色列产生切实后果的问题，并将拜登描述为以色列的终生朋友。</p><p>分析人士表示，拜登不太可能试图通过削减对以色列的援助来惩罚内塔尼亚胡，国会也可能不会支持这一举措。但以色列政府不太可能完全避免为这次投票付出代价。</p><p>华盛顿智库大西洋理事会非常驻研究员卡米尔·阿尔比特表示：“这将为国会中的人士提供素材，尤其是那些想要向拜登政府施压，要求其重新考虑两国关系的左翼人士。” “我不认为这会威胁到两国关系，但随着时间的推移，它会削弱这种关系。”</p><p><em>本说明性文章可能会定期更新。</em></p><p class="articleTagLine"> —Shayndi Raice、David S. Cloud 和 Ari Flanzraich 对本文做出了贡献。</p><p>写信给 Dov Lieber，邮箱为<a href="mailto:dov.lieber@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">dov.lieber@wsj.com</a></p></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Wed, 26 Jul 2023 13:00:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/israel-protests-judicial-overhaul-netanyahu-7e264a71</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/israel-protests-judicial-overhaul-netanyahu-7e264a71<author><![CDATA[Dov Lieber]]></author><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>国家/公共安全</category><category>政治/国际关系</category><category>国内政治</category><category>风险新闻</category><category>军事行动</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category>卡琳·让·皮埃尔</category><category>卡米尔仲裁</category><category>本杰明·内塔尼亚胡</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>国家的</category><category>公安</category><category>政治</category><category>国际关系</category><category>国内政治</category><category>风险新闻</category><category>军事行动</category></item><item><title><![CDATA[Israeli Supreme Court to Hear Challenge to Judicial Overhaul]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div> Court sets September date for preliminary hearing on constitutionality of law <!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001084207"><div class="is-lead-inset"><div class="media-object scope-
          header
"><figure class="media-object-image img-header"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="860" height="591" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-823613?width=860&amp;height=591" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">周二，在一项限制以色列最高法院权力的法案获得通过后，抗议者封锁了特拉维夫的一条高速公路。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：Corinna Kern/路透社</p></figcaption></figure></div></div></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001084207"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline"> <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/shayndi-raice" itemprop="url" rel="author">沙恩迪·赖斯</a></span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1">Updated July 26, 2023 8:14 am ET </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/israels-supreme-court-could-strike-down-a-bill-aimed-at-limiting-its-power-but-will-it-cc17a8d7"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><p> TEL AVIV—Israel&#39;s Supreme Court said Wednesday that it would hear a petition challenging the constitutionality of <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/israel-netanyahu-government-judicial-overhaul-protests-862dffd3?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">a judicial overhaul law enacted earlier this week</a> , setting up a possible showdown between the court and the government.</p><p> The court, however, didn&#39;t issue an immediate injunction, as petitioners had requested.</p><p> Nongovernmental organizations and others filed petitions asking Israel&#39;s highest court to overturn the law, which is akin to a constitutional amendment that does away with the court&#39;s power to strike down government decisions it determines are extremely unreasonable.最高法院从未做过这样的准宪法法律，但现在迫于公众压力却不得不这么做。</p><p> The court set a preliminary hearing, which will be heard by one justice, for September. The court can then decide to bring the case before an extended panel that could include as many as 11 justices.</p><p> The court&#39;s decision to set a hearing doesn&#39;t mean it will strike down the law—the question currently electrifying the country. Such a scenario would pit the government against the court and could lead to a full-blown constitutional crisis if the government were to ignore a court ruling.</p><p> The court&#39;s decision to set the hearing so quickly means “they understand the urgency,” said Yaniv Roznai, a law professor at Reichman University in the Israeli city of Herzliya. </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><div class="media-object-video"><div class="wsj-media-summary clearfix"><div class="strap-container"><h4 class="strap" itemprop="description"></h4></div></div><iframe width="400" height="225" src="https://video-api.wsj.com/api-video/player/v3/iframe.html?guid=B58B7540-4CF9-464C-A04F-C0E71926FD01&amp;height=225&amp;width=400&amp;plid=video_amp&amp;chainVideos=true&amp;parentUrl=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.wsj.com%2Famp%2Farticles%2Fisraels-supreme-court-could-strike-down-a-bill-aimed-at-limiting-its-power-but-will-it-cc17a8d7&amp;a=a" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe><p class="imageCaption">以色列医生周二举行罢工，当局在因总理本杰明·内塔尼亚胡政府进行的司法改革而发生骚乱的夜晚，强行将抗议者从道路上带走。照片：阿米尔·利维/盖蒂图片社<span class="imageCredit">
        
        
        </span></p></div></div><p>Eliad Shraga, chairman of the Movement for Quality Government in Israel, one of the groups that filed a petition, said the group was ready to defend Israeli democracy against what he described as a coup. “We will continue to demonstrate and fight everywhere and on every stage until the threat is removed!” he said in a statement.</p><p> Hundreds of thousands of Israelis <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/israeli-doctors-go-on-strike-to-protest-netanyahus-judicial-overhaul-463530e7?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">have protested</a> for more than six months against a plan by Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu&#39;s coalition to make sweeping changes to the judicial system.由于无法通过抗议、罢工和预备役军人威胁拒绝服役来阻止这项立法，反对者现在希望最高法院介入。</p><p> Israel&#39;s National Security Minister Itamar Ben-Gvir, a leader of the country&#39;s ultranationalist right, said that if the court strikes down the law, it would be “an attempted coup.”</p><div class="media-object scope-web
          wrap
"><div class="media-object-rich-text"><h4>分享你的意见</h4><p><em>以色列最高法院应如何应对限制其权力的新法律？加入下面的对话。</em></p></div></div><p>该法案周一由以色列议会通过，是旨在限制法院权力并赋予立法者更多控制权的更广泛立法中的第一个。内塔尼亚胡的联盟表示，法院由激进的自由派法官控制，立法旨在恢复适当的权力平衡。反对者指责这项立法将削弱法院对行政和立法权的制衡作用，并将侵蚀以色列的自由民主。</p><p>周一通过的法律是对以色列一项基本法律的修正案，该法律是多年来零碎通过的，是以色列最接近宪法的法律。虽然以色列最高法院从未废除过一项基本法，但它表示它有权力这样做。</p><p>法律学者表示，请愿者必须证明几件事才能让法院推翻这项法律。反对者必须证明该法律破坏了以色列作为犹太民主国家的核心价值观。他们还可以试图证明立法程序存在缺陷。</p><p>向法院提交请愿书的两个非政府组织以色列公民民主运动和达尔克努表示，该法律“对以色列民主的本质构成了严重和永久性的改变，这将摧毁民主政权所必需的制衡制度。” </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="466" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-823617?width=700&amp;height=466" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">总理本杰明·内塔尼亚胡周一出席了在耶路撒冷举行的以色列议会会议。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：玛雅·阿莱鲁佐/美联社</p></figcaption></figure></div><p></p>耶路撒冷希伯来大学法学教授约夫·多坦 (Yoav Dotan) 表示，从表面上看，这项法律似乎是允许以色列议会颁布的。<p></p><p> “如果你从纯粹的法律理论角度来处理这个问题，那么就没有明确的宪法依据来推翻这项立法，”多坦说。</p><p>但多坦和其他学者表示，法院可以考虑这样的背景：该法案是更广泛的司法改革中的第一个法案，旨在通过消除强有力的制衡制度来破坏民主。司法改革的反对者声称，该计划的目的是限制法院对行政部门和立法部门进行制衡的能力，而在以色列，由于议会政治的性质，行政部门和立法部门的关系非常密切。</p><p> “The court should look at the bigger picture because nowadays democracies do not die in a single law that says we are no longer a democracy,” said Roznai, the Reichman University professor. “如今的民主国家是在一个渐进的过程中一步步消亡的。” </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="467" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-823627?width=700&amp;height=467" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">抗议者周一在耶路撒冷示威反对政府的司法改革。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：Ronen Zvulun/路透社</p></figcaption></figure></div><p>许多法律学者表示，法院更有可能削弱该法律的影响，而不采取严厉措施废除该法律。</p><p>例如，法院可以简单地将法案退回议会，称其需要进一步辩论和另一次投票。</p><p>法官还可以利用其解释权来限制法律的范围。法院在解释 2018 年基本法时采用了这种方法，该法将以色列定义为“犹太人民的民族家园”，批评者称该法歧视以色列的阿拉伯公民。法院表示，只要该法律不与其他确立人权的基本法相抵触，该法律就适用。</p><p>周一通过的法案称，法院不能推翻政府的决定，因为它“极其不合理”。法律学者表示，法院可以决定采用不同术语的类似标准，例如美国使用的任意性和反复无常，或欧洲使用的相称性。</p><p> “法院不会废除这项法律，”多坦说。 “他们可以很容易地通过解释绕过该立法的大部分条款。”</p><p>罗兹奈表示，即使法院确实推翻了该法律，他也相信政府将遵守法院的裁决，以色列将避免真正的宪法危机。</p><p> “我无法想象以色列政府会违反这样的裁决，”他说。</p><p>写信给 Shayndi Raice，邮箱为<a href="mailto:Shayndi.Raice@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">Shayndi.Raice@wsj.com</a></p></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Wed, 26 Jul 2023 12:14:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/israels-supreme-court-could-strike-down-a-bill-aimed-at-limiting-its-power-but-will-it-cc17a8d7</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/israels-supreme-court-could-strike-down-a-bill-aimed-at-limiting-its-power-but-will-it-cc17a8d7<author><![CDATA[Shayndi Raice]]></author><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>国家/公共安全</category><category>犯罪/法律诉讼</category><category>政治/国际关系</category><category>国内政治</category><category>风险新闻</category><category>军事行动</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>国家的</category><category>公安</category><category>犯罪</category><category>合法举动</category><category>政治</category><category>国际关系</category><category>国内政治</category><category>风险新闻</category><category>军事行动</category></item></channel></rss>